(42, 1, '2018-06-30 00:51:41', '2018-06-30 00:51:41', '(rewrite in first-person)\r\n<h3>Background</h3>\r\nThe Liberty Bank Building is a community development built in the Central District (CD), on 24th &amp; Union st. This project is a unique and diverse partnership of many community members and groups that work together to make affordable housing more accessible to individuals, groups and families who are susceptible to the consequences of rapid urban development occurring in the CD.\r\n<h3>Design Problem &amp; Project Goals</h3>\r\nCurrent information about the leasing process for the Liberty Bank Building is complex, lengthy, and inaccessible to individuals most in need of this very information. Consequently, there has been misinformation spreading about how the application process works for the Liberty Bank Building.\r\n\r\nThe project goals are to clarify the eligibility requirements for affordable housing, explain the application process for leasing at the Liberty Bank Building, and affirmatively target audiences affected by rapidly rising rent in the CD. This will be achieved through a leasing packet design that is intuitive and\r\nsimply explains the affordable housing application process, and will include the following deliverables:\r\n<h3>Deliverables</h3>\r\n(a single packet of the following items)\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Overview / timeline document, (similar to the one produced by NY Housing Connect )</li>\r\n 	<li>FAQs document</li>\r\n 	<li>General leasing flyer with building features, photos, location map, and income requirements</li>\r\n 	<li>Income limit sheet (similar to the one produced by NY Housing Connect )</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Successes &amp; Failures</h3>\r\n<h4>Audience</h4>\r\n<h5>Primary</h5>\r\nIndividuals and families living in the CD who qualify for affordable housing and those who are looking for clear information on the leasing process and how to apply for the Liberty Bank Building affordable housing units.\r\n<h5>Secondary</h5>\r\nCommunity members and small businesses, particularly of pan-african decent, affected by displacement in the CD; or those individuals and community partners at risk of being unable to afford rapid rent increases in the CD’s housing and commercial real estate market.\r\n<h4>Relationships</h4>\r\n<h5>Client – LBB Building Partners</h5>\r\nThe Capitol Hill Housing Association ensures their approach to each community building is both intentional and affective in targeting individuals in need of affordable housing. For this project the Liberty Bank Partners _____.\r\n(something about how this collateral strengthened the LBB partners trust in CHH’s ability to be aware of its context and deliver content that is relevant to this project’s audience).\r\n<h5>Client – Designer</h5>\r\nThe client will primarily be a resource for information, questions, and any background material required for the designer to create the requested deliverables. The client and their affiliates will also serve as a\r\ncritical observer of all copy and design material. The client will share responsibility in previewing the copy and designed deliverables throughout the design process, including critical points in the timeline\r\nlike presentations and check-ins. Communications will be carried out over email, phone, and in person.\r\n<h3>The Impact</h3>\r\n*** EDIT ***', 'The Liberty Bank Building', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '16-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-06-30 00:51:41', '2018-06-30 00:51:41', '', 16, 'http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/16-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(43, 1, '2018-06-30 00:53:14', '2018-06-30 00:53:14', 'Capitol Hill Housing (CHH) is a public corporation organized by the City of Seattle. Their mission is to build vibrant and engaged communities through affordable housing and community development. They own and manage 48 affordable properties throughout the Seattle area, serving low- and moderate-income residents and work to improve neighborhoods for all of Seattle since 1976.\r\n<h2>The Resident Services Department</h2>\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Resident Services at Capitol Hill Housing exists to provide its residents with community resources, referrals to supportive services, and community support for each building and property.</span>\r\n<h3>Design problems</h3>\r\n<h4>Awareness</h4>\r\nThe Senior Communications Manager at CHH, Ashwin Warrior, contacted me in need of some brand collateral development for the Resident Services department. After a completing a survey of property residents, CHH found that a majority of residents were not aware that CHH offers additional services through their Resident Service Coordinators. We presumed this lack of awareness was in part due to their inconsistent templates and methods used to reaching residents.\r\n<h4>Accessibility and Consistency</h4>\r\nAnother concern Ashwin approached me about was their reliance on Microsoft Word templates. This was a problem because these same templates were being used by other City government entities, like the Public Library. This overlap in branding between government agencies clouded the CHH brand and was a key factor in CHH wanting to unify their brand image and messaging in order to stand up for the community.\r\n\r\nResident Services Coordinators (RSC) are the central resource for residents living in CHH properties. RSC’s will help residents with anything from answering a community question, hosting a community event, to receiving need based services like rental assistance, live-in health care, transportation services, and much more.\r\n\r\nGiven the broad scope of services and experience, it was paramount to create a templates that anyone could open and use on any computer, without much knowledge of typography and design layout, while still creating something unique to their community building and consistent with the larger CHH brand. These templates needed to be easily accessible/editable, simply formatted, and customizable for RSC’s to implement in each of their unique communities.\r\n<h3>Design Solution</h3>\r\nAshwin outlined five key collateral items the RSC\'s used most:\r\n\r\n[scroller]\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-32 size-large" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/poster_resident-services-e1530318746544-834x1024.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="786" /><img class="alignnone wp-image-34 size-large" style="font-family: -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, \'Segoe UI\', Roboto, Oxygen-Sans, Ubuntu, Cantarell, \'Helvetica Neue\', sans-serif;" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/tmpl_individual-rsc-768x1024.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="853" />\r\nA general welcome sheet given new residents that informs them about Capitol Hill Housing (CHH) and the resources that are available to them through the Resident Services program, and a Resident Service Coordinator (RSC) welcome sheet that introduces the individual RS Coordinator for the resident\'s property. Both these documents are provided to new residents upon moving in. It includes essential resources in addition to CHH and RSC\'s contact information.\r\n[/scroller]\r\n\r\n[scroller]\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-35 size-large" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/tmpl_residence-calendar-e1530319018147-1024x803.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="502" />\r\nA monthly calendar specific to each building property that shows all events and key date for the property residents to be aware of. The monthly calendars are posted on community boards in public building spaces.\r\n[/scroller]\r\n\r\n[scroller]\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-33 size-large" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/tmpl_event-flyers-e1530319332673-797x1024.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="822" />\r\nEvent flyers are posted in community spaces to advertise for major events. RSC\'s also create print-off half-sheet handouts for local, building specific events, and are posted in building community spaces and on residency doors.\r\n[/scroller]\r\n\r\n[scroller]\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-36 size-large" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/tmpl_resource-one-sheet-e1530319531779-819x1024.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="800" />\r\nA Resource One Sheet template that lists all relevant contact information for each resource category.\r\n[/scroller]\r\n\r\n<h3>Successes &amp; Failures</h3>\r\nIn our first meeting, Ashwin noted that the RSC’s primary means of communicating with residents is through community board postings and door-to-door tactics.\r\n<h4>Collateral</h4>\r\n<h5>general Resident Services poster</h5>\r\nto advertise CHH Resident Services, to be used primarily for awareness and placemaking\r\n<h5>calendar template</h5>\r\nspecific to each RSC and property\r\n<h5>building welcome template</h5>\r\ngiven to new residents to make them aware of the Resident Services available upon request\r\n<h5>persona template for each RSC</h5>\r\ngiven to new residents in a move in packet\r\n<h5>event ad templates</h5>\r\nused for a variety of community events and workshops; key variables included recurrent events and event sign ups\r\n<h3>The Impact</h3>\r\nThe general response from the CHH Resident Service Coordinators was positive.', 'Capitol Hill Housing', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '23-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-06-30 00:53:14', '2018-06-30 00:53:14', '', 23, 'http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/23-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
