ge-49" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE_Resident-Services-poster_11x17.jpg" alt="" />\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-50" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE_resource-one-sheet_8.5x11.jpg" alt="" />\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-53" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE-calendar_11x8.5.jpg" alt="" />\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-51" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE_welcome-sheetgeneral_8.5x11.jpg" alt="" />\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-52" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE_welcome-sheetJoeyG_8.5x11.jpg" alt="" />\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-48" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE_event-poster_8.5x11.jpg" alt="" />\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-47" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/BLANK_event-flyer_x2_5.5x8.5.jpg" alt="" />\r\n[/scroller]\r\n\r\n<h4>Resident Services Poster</h4>\r\nIn addition to the five collateral templates Ashwin provided me, we proposed to design a large format poster to use to advertise to residents. We proposed to mount these on community boards in public building spaces, around the building property, and will be used primarily to inform residents of the services available. It also supported resident place-making; by giving the CHH property a uniform image, residents are projected to understand the network of support provided by CHH and RSC\'s.\r\n\r\n<h4>Resource One Sheet Template</h4>\r\nThe template is very similar to the original template. From the beginning I worked out a typographic system and grid layout that is adaptable to each collateral template created. This one sheet example is the simplest form of typography and grid layout used across all the templates.\r\n\r\n<h4>Calendar Template</h4>\r\nAfter creating a 2018-19 monthly calendar template with updated styles, I added additional content to the footer, specific to each RSC and property. This allowed each RSC to put their contact information and the building information on the calendar.\r\n\r\n<h4>Building Welcome Template</h4>\r\nThe general  building welcome sheet is given to new residents and includes a welcoming message, important contact information, and more detailed information along a sidebar.\r\n\r\n<h4>Welcome Home, RSC Persona Template</h4>\r\nThe RSC persona template is similar to the building welcome template. It is also given to new residents in a move in packet, and contains an inviting introduction plus essential contact information.\r\n\r\n<h4>event ad templates</h4>\r\nThe event templates are used for a variety of community events and workshops. Consequentially, I designed a variable sidebar layout for things like recurrent event dates and event sign ups. RSC\'s are able to choose between having a single event data or multiple recurring events. Additionally, there is an option for a sign-up content block with a variable height allowing for more or less sign-up lines.\r\n\r\nI also made a print-off half-sheet event template that synthesizes event information to its primary message and call to action.\r\n\r\n<h3>Design Impact</h3>\r\nThe general response from the CHH Resident Service Coordinators was positive.\r\n<h3>Successes &amp; Failures</h3>\r\nAccording to the 2016 CHH annual resident survey, less than half all residents in CHH properties are aware that CHH provides individualize support through their Resident Services program. With this in mind, the primary goal was to design content that informed residents of their Resident Services Coordinators and the Resident Services available through CHH. In order to achieve this, I thought strategically about the visual design and the delivery methods to optimize the RSC\'s collateral rebrand impact.\r\n<h4>Visual Design</h4>\r\nCHH manages about 50 separate properties each with individual eligibility requirements that support a range of residents from, low-income, elderly, disabled, veterans, and other eligibility restricted units. The potential viewing audience for this project spans generations of experience and understand. Given this, I did not want the visual content to distract at all from the text content. More importantly, the text content needed to be simplified to its critical points and written in a way that is accessible to the diverse audience. <strong>(Did I succeed?)</strong>\r\n<h4>Delivery Methods</h4>\r\nThe RS Coordinator\'s primary means of communication with property residents is through information sheets and advertisements given out at CHH offices, community boards in public building spaces on CHH properties, door-to-door tactics and community building events, and through one on one contact with RSC\'s.', 'Capitol Hill Housing', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '23-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-06-30 03:39:58', '2018-06-30 03:39:58', '', 23, 'http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/23-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(65, 1, '2018-06-30 03:42:27', '2018-06-30 03:42:27', 'Capitol Hill Housing (CHH) is a public corporation organized by the City of Seattle. Their mission is to build vibrant and engaged communities through affordable housing and community development. They own and manage 48 affordable properties throughout the Seattle area, serving low- and moderate-income residents and work to improve neighborhoods for all of Seattle since 1976.\r\n<h2>The Resident Services Department</h2>\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Resident Services at Capitol Hill Housing exists to provide its residents with community resources, referrals to supportive services, and community support for each building and property.</span>\r\n<h3>Design problems</h3>\r\n<h4>Awareness</h4>\r\nThe Senior Communications Manager at CHH, Ashwin Warrior, contacted me in need of some brand collateral development for the Resident Services department. After a completing a survey of property residents, CHH found that a majority of residents were not aware that CHH offers additional services through their Resident Service Coordinators. We presumed this lack of awareness was in part due to their inconsistent templates and methods used to reaching residents.\r\n<h4>Accessibility and Consistency</h4>\r\nAnother concern Ashwin approached me about was their reliance on Microsoft Word templates. This was a problem because these same templates were being used by other City government entities, like the Public Library. This overlap in branding between government agencies clouded the CHH brand and was a key factor in CHH wanting to unify their brand image and messaging in order to stand up for the community.\r\n\r\nResident Services Coordinators (RSC) are the central resource for residents living in CHH properties. RSC’s will help residents with anything from answering a community question, hosting a community event, to receiving need based services like rental assistance, live-in health care, transportation services, and muc