(75, 1, '2018-06-30 05:19:30', '2018-06-30 05:19:30', 'Capitol Hill Housing (CHH) is a public corporation organized by the City of Seattle. Their mission is to build vibrant and engaged communities through affordable housing and community development. They own and manage 48 affordable properties throughout the Seattle area, serving low- and moderate-income residents and work to improve neighborhoods for all of Seattle since 1976.\r\n<h2>The Resident Services Department</h2>\r\nResident Services at Capitol Hill Housing exists to provide its residents with community resources, referrals to supportive services, and community support for each building and property.\r\n<h3>Design Background</h3>\r\nCHH manages about 50 separate properties each with individual eligibility requirements that support a range of residents from, low-income, elderly, disabled, veterans, and other eligibility restricted units. The potential viewing audience for this project spans generations of experience and understanding.\r\n\r\nCHH uses Site Managers to help manage properties and Resident Service Coordinator\'s (RSC) to inform, coordinate and provide a variety of resources for residents.\r\n\r\nThe RSC\'s primary means of communication with property residents is through information sheets and advertisements given out at CHH offices, community boards in public building spaces on CHH properties, door-to-door tactics and community building events, and through one on one contact with RSC\'s.\r\n<h3>Design problems</h3>\r\n<h4>Awareness</h4>\r\nThe Senior Communications Manager at CHH, Ashwin Warrior, contacted me in need of some brand collateral development for the Resident Services department. After a completing a survey of property residents, CHH found that a majority of residents were not aware that CHH offers additional services through their Resident Service Coordinators. We presumed this lack of awareness was in part due to their inconsistent templates and delivery methods used to reaching residents.\r\n<h4>Accessibility and Consistency</h4>\r\nAnother concern Ashwin approached me about was their reliance on Microsoft Word templates. This was a problem because these same templates were being used by other City government entities, like the Public Library. This overlap in branding between government agencies clouded the CHH brand and was a key factor in CHH wanting to unify their brand image and messaging in order to stand up for the community.\r\n\r\nResident Services Coordinators (RSC) are the central resource for residents living in CHH properties. RSC’s will help residents with anything from answering a community question, hosting a community event, to receiving need based services like rental assistance, live-in health care, transportation services, and much more.\r\n\r\nGiven the broad scope of services and experience, it was paramount to create a templates that anyone could open and use on any computer, without much knowledge of typography and design layout, while still creating something unique to their community building and consistent with the larger CHH brand. These templates needed to be easily accessible/editable, simply formatted, and customizable for RSC’s to implement in each of their unique communities.\r\n<h3>Existing Collateral</h3>\r\nAshwin presented me with five collateral items the RSC\'s used most:\r\n\r\n[scroller]<img class="alignnone wp-image-32 size-large" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/poster_resident-services-e1530318746544-834x1024.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="786" /><img class="alignnone wp-image-34 size-large" style="font-family: -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, \'Segoe UI\', Roboto, Oxygen-Sans, Ubuntu, Cantarell, \'Helvetica Neue\', sans-serif;" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/tmpl_individual-rsc-768x1024.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="853" /><img class="alignnone wp-image-35 size-large" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/tmpl_residence-calendar-e1530319018147-1024x803.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="502" /><img class="alignnone wp-image-33 size-large" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/tmpl_event-flyers-e1530319332673-797x1024.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="822" /><img class="alignnone wp-image-36 size-large" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/tmpl_resource-one-sheet-e1530319531779-819x1024.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="800" />[/scroller]\r\n<h4>Information and Welcome Sheets</h4>\r\nA general welcome sheet given new residents that informs them about Capitol Hill Housing (CHH) and the resources that are available to them through the Resident Services program, and a Resident Service Coordinator (RSC) welcome sheet that introduces the individual RS Coordinator for the resident\'s property. Both these documents are provided to new residents upon moving in. It includes essential resources in addition to CHH and RSC\'s contact information.\r\n<h4>Monthly Event Calendar</h4>\r\nA monthly calendar specific to each building property that shows all events and key date for the property residents to be aware of. The monthly calendars are posted on community boards in public building spaces.\r\n<h4>Event Flyers</h4>\r\nEvent flyers are posted in community spaces to advertise for major events. RSC\'s also create print-off half-sheet handouts for local, building specific events, and are posted in building community spaces and on residency doors.\r\n<h4>Resource One Sheets</h4>\r\nA template that lists all relevant contact information for each resource category.\r\n<h3>Design Solutions</h3>\r\nThe unique challenge to this project was designing templates using Adobe InDesign but then making those template accessible to users who do not use InDesign regularly and go not have a background in design. I learned that CHH uses Adobe Acrobat which has excellent capability with InDesign. By exporting the templates as an <em>interactive PDF</em>, any RSC may copy the template PDF and edit the image and text content while maintain consistency across the branding.\r\n<h4>Deliverables</h4>\r\nEach of the below templates have the customizable features:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>CHH brand color schemes and font options</li>\r\n 	<li>text blocks that maintain text styles</li>\r\n 	<li>image blocks maintain position and crop boundary, but allow custom image scaling and positioning within the crop boundary</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[scroller]\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-49" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE_Resident-Services-poster_11x17.jpg" alt="" />\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-50" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE_resource-one-sheet_8.5x11.jpg" alt="" />\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-53" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE-calendar_11x8.5.jpg" alt="" />\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-51" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE_welcome-sheetgeneral_8.5x11.jpg" alt="" />\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-52" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE_welcome-sheetJoeyG_8.5x11.jpg" alt="" />\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-48" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE_event-poster_8.5x11.jpg" alt="" />\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-47" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/BLANK_event-flyer_x2_5.5x8.5.jpg" alt="" />\r\n[/scroller]\r\n<h4>Resident Services Poster</h4>\r\nIn addition to the five collateral templates Ashwin provided me, we proposed to design a large format poster to use to advertise to residents. We proposed to mount these on community boards in public building spaces, around the building property, and will be used primarily to inform residents of the services available. It also supported resident place-making; by giving the CHH property a uniform image, residents are projected to understand the network of support provided by CHH and RSC\'s.\r\n<h4>Resource One Sheet Template</h4>\r\nThe template is very similar to the original template. From the beginning I worked out a typographic system and grid layout that is adaptable to each collateral template created. This one sheet example is the simplest form of typography and grid layout used across all the templates.\r\n<h4>Calendar Template</h4>\r\nAfter creating a 2018-19 monthly calendar template with updated styles, I added additional content to the footer, specific to each RSC and property. This allowed each RSC to put their contact information and the building information on the calendar.\r\n<h4>Building Welcome Template</h4>\r\nThe general  building welcome sheet is given to new residents and includes a welcoming message, important contact information, and more detailed information along a sidebar.\r\n<h4>Welcome Home, RSC Persona Template</h4>\r\nThe RSC persona template is similar to the building welcome template. It is also given to new residents in a move in packet, and contains an inviting introduction plus essential contact information.\r\n<h4>Event Ad Templates</h4>\r\nThe event templates are used for a variety of community events and workshops. Consequentially, I designed a variable sidebar layout for things like recurrent event dates and event sign ups. RSC\'s are able to choose between having a single event data or multiple recurring events. Additionally, there is an option for a sign-up content block with a variable height allowing for more or less sign-up lines.\r\n\r\nI also made a print-off half-sheet event template that synthesizes event information to its primary message and call to action.\r\n<h3>Design Impact</h3>\r\nThe general response from Ashwin, the CHH employees, Resident Service Coordinators and few residents was overwhelmingly positive. Given the visual design of collateral prior to my involvement, the impression of the deliverables exceeded the established expectations.\r\n\r\nAccording to the 2016 CHH annual resident survey, less than half all residents in CHH properties are aware that CHH provides individualize support through their Resident Services program. With this in mind, we established three goals to guide the design. 1) to informs residents of the Resident Services Coordinators and make them aware of the Resident Services available through CHH, 2) to re-design collateral templates, to simplify the layout to be consistent with the CHH brand, and 3) to improve collateral accessibility, both for the RSC\'s using the templates to create collateral and for a diverse audience of residents. In order to achieve these goals, I thought strategically about the visual design and the delivery methods to optimize the RSC\'s collateral rebrand impact.\r\n<h4>Visual Design</h4>\r\nHow did this help achieve the goals above?\r\n\r\nI did not want the visual content to distract at all from the text content. More importantly, the text content needed to be simplified to its critical points and written in a way that is accessible to the diverse audience.\r\n<h4>Delivery Methods</h4>\r\n&nbsp;', 'Capitol Hill Housing', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '23-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-06-30 05:19:30', '2018-06-30 05:19:30', '', 23, 'http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/23-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ;
