(148, 1, '2018-07-04 23:47:06', '2018-07-04 23:47:06', '<span style="font-weight: 400">I strive to be a reliable digital designer who learns fast and enjoys organization. I excel at composing and formulating information into clear visuals that demonstrate mature application of design theory and practice. With a diverse background in digital and print design, I work with local businesses to develop impact driven collateral including marketing tools, brand assets, templates, presentations and visual strategies.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400">My experience working with a startup, an architecture studio, designing for Seattle businesses, and serving on a 501(c)(3) board as the Design and Marketing Chair, allowed me the opportunity to gain in depth knowledge about the professional and creative sides of design.</span>\n<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">People tell me I am good at</span></h2>\n<h3><span style="font-weight: 400">Asking Questions</span></h3>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400">My process is driven by curiosity. I address challenges creatively by asking questions first. Afterwards, I thoroughly research target markets, audience demographics, typography and design patterns. At the same time, hand sketching and photographic moodboards compliment my research. This part of my process inspires further conceptual development and helps me understand the variables involved — to properly execute a visual strategy that achieves the project goals.</span>\n<h3><span style="font-weight: 400">Iteration &amp; Variation</span></h3>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400">I use an iterative design process to explore many design concepts. Team critiques are an important component to iteration. It opens up dialogue between the design concept and its stakeholders. Brainstorming is another tactic I utilize in my workflow to help teams visual and orient towards a central vision. These conversations inform my process and serve further conceptual development.</span>\n<h3><span st