></h4>\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Consistency affects people’s awareness and trust of a brand. If residents aren’t clear what the RSC provide and who they are in relation to CHH, then they are likely to have less faith in the services provided. I directly addressed this issue through a systematically implemented visual design. Through use of typography, white space, graphic elements and color, I achieved overall visual consistency between each collateral template.</span>\r\n<h4><b>Accessibility</b></h4>\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">The visual design compliments the content strategy and does not detract from it. We simplified the text and used language understood by a general audience. I also utilized a relatively large font size to improve legibility for residents with visual impairments. Attention was also paid to color usage, to increase accessibility for color visually impaired people.</span>\r\n<h4><b>Usability</b></h4>\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">To provide maximum ease of use for the RSC, who may not have a background in design or layout programs, I chose Adobe InDesign to make the templates. The Adobe InDesign has excellent interface with Adobe Acrobat, the program used by the majority of CHH employees. This has resulted in great ease of use for the RSC, allowing for editable content while maintaining overall brand consistency and increased design awareness.</span>\r\n<h3><b>Project Results</b></h3>\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">The overall response from the Client, CHH employees, Resident Service Coordinators and residents was overwhelming positive. The visual design and functionality of my project deliverables exceeded their expectations. In fact, after using the new templates, several RSC requested more variations for the event flyers, resulting in additional project work. In recreating these design pieces for CHH, I created a visual design similar enough to the existing look to maintain the familiarity of the old styles, while drastically improving brand accessibility, functionality, consistency and awareness. Our focus on content strategy, language and visual harmony allowed the simple style to accommodate the diverse audiences with propriety and appeal.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">[scroller]<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-71" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/IMG_3094_small.jpg" alt="Capitol Hill Housing community event" /> <img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-90" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/IMG_2666-768x1024.jpg" alt="" /> <img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-89" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/IMG_2499-1024x768.jpg" alt="" /> <img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-70" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CAPHILLHOUSING-186-1-1024x683.jpg" alt="Ashwin Warrior enters the Capitol Hill Housing offices on 12th Ave." />[/scroller]</span>', 'Capitol Hill Housing Resident Services', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '23-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-07-07 02:44:16', '2018-07-07 02:44:16', '', 23, 'http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/23-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(160, 1, '2018-04-30 12:00:49', '2018-04-30 12:00:49', 'For the Capitol Hill Housing leasing department, I conceptualized, designed and developed a leasing packet for an affordable housing development in the Central District called the Liberty Bank Building. The building is a multi-use apartment complex with entirely low-income eligible units and over 2,500 square feet of commercial space for local businesses. It is currently under construction and scheduled to open February 2019.\r\n<h3>Background</h3>The Liberty Bank Building is the result of a collective partnership between Africa Town Central District, Byrd Barr Place, Black Community Impact Alliance, the Capitol Hill Housing Foundation, local community leaders and founders of the Liberty Bank. This historic project aspires to preserve the legacy of <em>the Liberty Bank</em>, "the first Black-owned bank west of the Mississippi, founded as a community response to redlining and disinvestment in Central Seattle" (libertybankbuilding.org).\r\n\r\nHistorically, the City government divested from the Central District. This segregated community became a hub for pan-African and migrant community culture. Today it is experiencing rapid urban development, and as rent increases faster than the existing community members are able to afford, they become displaced from their homes.\r\n\r\nThe Liberty Bank Building is designed to be affordable for everyday people, and continues to support the community for years to come. We wanted to highlight this legacy, preserve the existing identity of the Central District, and steward in a new generation of community engagement.\r\n<h3>Project Challenges &amp; Goals</h3>Existing Liberty Bank material, while resourceful, was lengthy and complex, making it impractical for the target audience. A key assignment for this project was to create leasing content that would be understandable and usable for <em>all members</em> of the community—<em>it needed to be accessible</em>.\r\n\r\nThe leasing packet design was heavily influenced by all these factors. The project goals were:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>to clarify the eligibility requirements for affordable housing</li>\r\n 	<li>walk applicants through the leasing process and timeline for the Liberty Bank Building</li>\r\n 	<li>affirmatively market to audiences affected by rapid urbanization in the Central District</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Design Strategy</h3>The design needed to be tailored to a broad range of audience segments. The primary audience was individuals and families living in the Central District who qualify for affordable housing. The secondary audience was community members and small businesses, particularly of pan-African decent, affected by rapidly rising rent. The third audience, was public officials, agencies, and organization who work in the housing marketplace.\r\n\r\nTo clarify the eligibility requirements for affordable housing and walk applicants through the leasing process, I neatly organized complex leasing information in a format accessible to a broad audience whom are largely unfamiliar with affordable housing regulation in Seattle, but have a deeply rooted history in the Central District.\r\n<h3>Design Solution</h3>[scroller bg-color="LightSlateGrey"]\r\n<img src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-refinements_spread_1.jpg" class="alignnone wp-image-307 size-full" height="1650" alt="" width="1275"><img src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-refinements_spread_2.jpg" class="alignnone wp-image-308 size-full" height="1650" alt="" width="2550"><img src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-refinements_spread_3.jpg" class="alignnone wp-image-309 size-full" height="1650" alt="" width="2550"><img src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-refinements_spread_4.jpg" class="alignnone wp-image-310 size-full" height="1650" alt="" width="2550"><img src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-refinements_spread_5.jpg" class="alignnone wp-image-311 size-full" alt="">\r\n[/scroller]\r\n\r\n<!--[column_wrap count="4"]\r\n[column span="1"][fullscreen view="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-refinements_spread_1.jpg"]Cover[/fullscreen][/column]\r\n[column span="1"][fullscreen view="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-refinements_spread_2.jpg"]About LBB[/fullscreen][/column]\r\n[column span="1"][fullscreen view="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-refinements_spread_3.jpg"]Leasing Process[/fullscreen][/column]\r\n[column span="1"][fullscreen view="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-refinements_spread_4.jpg"]FAQs[/fullscreen][/column]\r\n[/column_wrap]-->\r\n\r\nThe Capitol Hill Housing Foundation hired me to deliver a single leasing packet of the following items:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>General building information including amenities, photos, and location map</li>\r\n 	<li>Affordable housing process overview</li>\r\n 	<li>Income requirements for applying</li>\r\n 	<li>A timeline of the project development and leasing process</li>\r\n 	<li>Frequently Asked Questions sheet</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Design Process</h3>Leasing affordable housing differs from non-subsidized apartments; and the Liberty Bank Building itself poses a unique application process. While focusing on conceptual development with moodboards, typography and color schemes, I worked with the team to categorize, synthesize and tailor content strategically.\r\n\r\nThe visual design is intuitive and simply explains affordable housing, the application process, and eligibility requirements use accessible language. Visual graphs and tables help applicants interactively determine their eligibility, while a four step visual breakdown walks them through the leasing process.\r\n\r\nWe sourced historic photos from the Liberty Bank partners, and composed them with photos of the new Liberty Bank Building. I coordinated with the client to render a more diverse group of people in the building renderings. I was sure to prioritize contact information; and developed a Frequently Asked Questions spread. I also included a timeline of key dates for the project construction and leasing process.\r\n<h3>Project Impact</h3>The layout itself is a huge improvement from the single word document the partners began with. Including photos of the historic Central District and current community events, drastically improved the packet\'s relatability. The use of visual motifs, typographic hierarchy and layout, and brand consistency were driving forces behind achieving project goals.\r\n\r\nThe partners responded very positively to the leasing packet design. The project delivered on schedule and within budget. Once the Liberty Bank Building partners begin actively marketing, it is anticipated this leasing packet will allow local community members to become more familiar with the affordable housing application process and give them the confidence to inquire about living at the Liberty Bank Building.\r\n\r\nThe Liberty Bank Building partners utilized the leasing packet to affirmatively market to audiences affected by rapid urbanization. They plan to host local events to build community and pass out these leasing packets to residents in need. The visual design compliments their marketing tactics in a way that communicates the history of the Liberty Bank, expresses the future tone of the Liberty Bank Building, and respects the pan-African community in the Central District.\r\n<h3>Sources</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><a href="http://libertybankbuilding.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Liberty Bank Building</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href="http://www.africatownlandtrust.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Africa Town Land Trust, Central District</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href="https://byrdbarrplace.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Byrd Barr Place</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href="http://david-harris-wkj7.squarespace.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Black Community Impact Alliance</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href="https://www.capitolhillhousing.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Capitol Hill Housing Foundation</a></li>\r\n</ul>', 'The Liberty Bank Building', 'For the Capitol Hill Housing leasing department, I conceptualized, designed and developed a leasing packet for an affordable housing development in the Central District called the Liberty Bank Building.', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'the-liberty-bank-building', '', '', '2018-07-25 19:41:52', '2018-07-25 19:41:52', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/?p=160', 0, 'post', '', 0),
