(163, 1, '2018-07-07 02:48:49', '2018-07-07 02:48:49', '<span style="font-weight: 400;">For the Capitol Hill Housing leasing department, I conceptualized, designed and developed a leasing packet for an affordable housing development in the Central District called the Liberty Bank Building. The building is a multi-use apartment complex with entirely low-income eligible units and over 2,500 square feet of commercial space for local businesses. It is currently under construction and set to open in February 2019.</span>\r\n<h3><b>Background</b></h3>\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">The Liberty Bank Building is the result of a collective partnership between Africa Town Central District, Byrd Barr Place, Black Community Impact Alliance, the Capitol HIll Housing Foundation, local community leaders and founders of the Liberty Bank. This historic project aspires to preserve the legacy of the first black-owned bank west of the Mississippi by continuing to support the community for years to come. We wanted to highlight this legacy, preserve the existing identity of the Central District, and steward in a new generation of community engagement.</span>\r\n<h3><b>Project Challenges &amp; Goals</b></h3>\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Historically, the Seattle City government divested from the Central District. This segregated community became a hub for pan african and migrant community culture. Today it is experiencing rapid urban development. As rent increases faster than the existing community members are able to afford, they become displaced from their homes. The Liberty Bank Bank building will provide affordable housing for these very residents, in a continued effort to preserve the Central District’s cultural identity.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Capitol Hill Housing provided me a single microsoft word document with all existing information about the leasing process for the Liberty Bank Building. It contained complex language, had a lengthy format, and was largely inaccessible to individuals most in need of this very information. Consequently the inaccessibility of this information led to rumors being spread about the project development and its leasing process.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">The leasing packet design was heavily influenced by all these factors. The scoped project goals were:</span>\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">to clarify the eligibility requirements for affordable housing,</span></li>\r\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">walk applicants through the leasing process and timeline for the Liberty Bank Building,</span></li>\r\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">and affirmatively market to audiences affected by rapid urbanization in the Central District.</span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h3><b>Design Strategy</b></h3>\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">A major variable for the The Liberty Bank Building leasing packet is the differing audience segments I needed to tailor the design to. The primary audience is individuals and families living in the Central District who qualify for affordable housing and those looking for information on the leasing process and how to apply for the Liberty Bank Building. The secondary audience is community members and small businesses, particularly of pan-african decent, affected by displacement in the Central District; or those individuals and community partners at risk of being unable to afford rapid rent increases in the housing and commercial real estate market.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">In order to clarify the eligibility requirements for affordable housing and walk applicants through the leasing process, I neatly organized complex leasing information in a format accessible to a broad audience whom are largely unfamiliar with affordable housing regulation in Seattle.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">The Liberty Bank Building partners will utilize the leasing packet to affirmatively market to audiences affected by rapid urbanization by hosting local community events in which these leasing packets will be distributed to local residents. We intend partnered staff to be present, answering questions on site. The visual design compliments their marketing tactics in a way that communicates the history of the Liberty Bank, expresses the future tone of the Liberty Bank Building, and un-offensively appreciates and respects the pan-african community in the Central District.</span>\r\n<h3><b>Design Solution</b></h3>\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">[scroller] LBB Leasing Packet Slideshow [/scroller]</span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">The Capitol Hill Housing Foundation hired me to deliver a single leasing packet of the following items:</span>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">General building information like amenities, photos, and location map</span></li>\r\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Affordable housing process overview</span></li>\r\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Income requirements for applying</span></li>\r\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">A timeline of the project development and leasing</span></li>\r\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Frequently Asked Questions</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3><b>Design Process</b></h3>\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Leasing affordable housing differs from non-subsidized apartments; and the Liberty Bank Building itself poses a unique application process. While focusing on conceptual development with moodboards, typography and color schemes, I worked with the partners team to effortlessly to categorize, synthesize and tailored content strategically.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">The visual design is intuitive and simply explains affordable housing, the application process, and eligibility requirements using accessible language. Visual graphs and tables help applicants interactively determine their eligibility, while a four step visual breakdown walks them through the leasing process. We sourced historic photos from the Liberty Bank partners, and composed them with photos of the new Liberty Bank Building. We even coordinated with the architect to render a more diverse group of people in the building renderings. I was sure to prioritize contact information; and in case anyone has additional questions, a subsequent spread contains Frequently Ask Questions. I also included a handy timeline of key dates for the project construction and leasing process.</span>\r\n<h3><b>Project Impact</b></h3>\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">The layout itself is a huge improvement from the single word document the partners began with. Including photos of the historic Central District and current community events, drastically improved the packets relatability to our target audience. The use of visual motifs, typographic hierarchy and layout, and brand consistency were driving forces behind achieving project goals.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">The Capitol Hill Housing Association ensures their approach to each community building is both intentional and affective in targeting individuals in need of affordable housing. Upon beginning this assignment, there were minor tensions rising between community partners as its construction progressed. The success of this collateral project strengthened the Liberty Bank Building partners’ trust in Capitol Hill Housings’ ability to be aware of its context and deliver content that is relevant to this project’s audience.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">The a vast majority of the partners responded very positively to the leasing packet design, with only minor tweaks to the cover needed after the fact. Overall the project delivered on schedule and within the partners budget. Once the Liberty Bank Building partners begin actively marketing, it is anticipated this leasing packet will allow local community members to become more familiar with the affordable housing application process and give them the confidence to inquire about living at the Liberty Bank Building.</span>\r\n<h3><b>Sources</b></h3>\r\n<a href="http://libertybankbuilding.org/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">http://libertybankbuilding.org/</span></a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.africatownlandtrust.org/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">http://www.africatownlandtrust.org/</span></a>\r\n\r\n<a href="https://byrdbarrplace.org/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://byrdbarrplace.org/</span></a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://david-harris-wkj7.squarespace.com/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">http://david-harris-wkj7.squarespace.com/</span></a>\r\n\r\n<a href="https://www.capitolhillhousing.org/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://www.capitolhillhousing.org/</span></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'The Liberty Bank Building', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '160-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-07-07 02:48:49', '2018-07-07 02:48:49', '', 160, 'http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/160-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
