(166, 1, '2018-07-24 22:02:56', '2018-07-24 22:02:56', 'For the Capitol Hill Housing leasing department, I conceptualized, designed and developed a leasing packet for an affordable housing development in the Central District called the Liberty Bank Building. The building is a multi-use apartment complex with entirely low-income eligible units and over 2,500 square feet of commercial space for local businesses. It is currently under construction and scheduled to open February 2019.\n<h3>Background</h3>\nThe Liberty Bank Building is the result of a collective partnership between Africa Town Central District, Byrd Barr Place, Black Community Impact Alliance, the Capitol Hill Housing Foundation, local community leaders and founders of the Liberty Bank. This historic project aspires to preserve the legacy of <em>the Liberty Bank</em>, "the first Black-owned bank west of the Mississippi, founded as a community response to redlining and disinvestment in Central Seattle" (libertybankbuilding.org).\n\nHistorically, the City government divested from the Central District. This segregated community became a hub for pan-African and migrant community culture. Today it is experiencing rapid urban development, and as rent increases faster than the existing community members are able to afford, they become displaced from their homes.\n\nThe Liberty Bank Building is designed to be affordable for everyday people, and continues to support the community for years to come. We wanted to highlight this legacy, preserve the existing identity of the Central District, and steward in a new generation of community engagement.\n<h3>Project Challenges &amp; Goals</h3>\nExisting Liberty Bank material, while resourceful, was lengthy and complex, making it impractical for the target audience. A key assignment for this project was to create leasing content that would be understandable and usable for <em>all members</em> of the community—<em>it needed to be accessible</em>.\n\nThe leasing packet design was heavily influenced by all these factors. The project goals were:\n<ul>\n 	<li>to clarify the eligibility requirements for affordable housing</li>\n 	<li>walk applicants through the leasing process and timeline for the Liberty Bank Building</li>\n 	<li>affirmatively market to audiences affected by rapid urbanization in the Central District</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Design Strategy</h3>\nThe design needed to be tailored to a broad range of audience segments. The primary audience was individuals and families living in the Central District who qualify for affordable housing. The secondary audience was community members and small businesses, particularly of pan-African decent, affected by rapidly rising rent. The third audience, was public officials, agencies, and organization who work in the housing marketplace.\n\nTo clarify the eligibility requirements for affordable housing and walk applicants through the leasing process, I neatly organized complex leasing information in a format accessible to a broad audience whom are largely unfamiliar with affordable housing regulation in Seattle, but have a deeply rooted history in the Central District.\n<h3>Design Solution</h3>\n[scroller bg-color="LightSlateGrey"]\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-307 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-refinements_spread_1.jpg" alt="" width="1275" height="1650" /><img class="alignnone wp-image-308 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-refinements_spread_2.jpg" alt="" width="2550" height="1650" /><img class="alignnone wp-image-309 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-refinements_spread_3.jpg" alt="" width="2550" height="1650" /><img class="alignnone wp-image-310 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-refinements_spread_4.jpg" alt="" width="2550" height="1650" /><img class="alignnone wp-image-311 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-refinements_spread_5.jpg" alt="" />\n[/scroller]\n\n[column_wrap count="4"]\n[column span="1"][fullscreen view="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-refinements_spread_1.jpg"]Cover[/fullscreen][/column]\n[column span="1"][fullscreen view="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-refinements_spread_2.jpg"]About the LBB[/fullscreen][/column]\n[column span="1"][fullscreen view="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-refinements_spread_3.jpg"]Leasing Process[/fullscreen][/column]\n[column span="1"][fullscreen view="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-refinements_spread_4.jpg"]FAQs[/fullscreen][/column]\n[/column_wrap]\n\nThe Capitol Hill Housing Foundation hired me to deliver a single leasing packet of the following items:\n<ul>\n 	<li>General building information including amenities, photos, and location map</li>\n 	<li>Affordable housing process overview</li>\n 	<li>Income requirements for applying</li>\n 	<li>A timeline of the project development and leasing process</li>\n 	<li>Frequently Asked Questions sheet</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Design Process</h3>\nLeasing affordable housing differs from non-subsidized apartments; and the Liberty Bank Building itself poses a unique application process. While focusing on conceptual development with moodboards, typography and color schemes, I worked with the team to categorize, synthesize and tailor content strategically.\n\nThe visual design is intuitive and simply explains affordable housing, the application process, and eligibility requirements use accessible language. Visual graphs and tables help applicants interactively determine their eligibility, while a four step visual breakdown walks them through the leasing process.\n\nWe sourced historic photos from the Liberty Bank partners, and composed them with photos of the new Liberty Bank Building. I coordinated with the client to render a more diverse group of people in the building renderings. I was sure to prioritize contact information; and developed a Frequently Asked Questions spread. I also included a timeline of key dates for the project construction and leasing process.\n<h3>Project Impact</h3>\nThe layout itself is a huge improvement from the single word document the partners began with. Including photos of the historic Central District and current community events, drastically improved the packet\'s relatability. The use of visual motifs, typographic hierarchy and layout, and brand consistency were driving forces behind achieving project goals.\n\nThe partners responded very positively to the leasing packet design. The project delivered on schedule and within budget. Once the Liberty Bank Building partners begin actively marketing, it is anticipated this leasing packet will allow local community members to become more familiar with the affordable housing application process and give them the confidence to inquire about living at the Liberty Bank Building.\n\nThe Liberty Bank Building partners utilized the leasing packet to affirmatively market to audiences affected by rapid urbanization. They plan to host local events to build community and pass out these leasing packets to residents in need. The visual design compliments their marketing tactics in a way that communicates the history of the Liberty Bank, expresses the future tone of the Liberty Bank Building, and respects the pan-African community in the Central District.\n<h3>Sources</h3>\n<ul>\n 	<li><a href="http://libertybankbuilding.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Liberty Bank Building</a></li>\n 	<li><a href="http://www.africatownlandtrust.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Africa Town Land Trust, Central District</a></li>\n 	<li><a href="https://byrdbarrplace.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Byrd Barr Place</a></li>\n 	<li><a href="http://david-harris-wkj7.squarespace.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Black Community Impact Alliance</a></li>\n 	<li><a href="https://www.capitolhillhousing.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Capitol Hill Housing Foundation</a></li>\n</ul>', 'The Liberty Bank Building', 'For the Capitol Hill Housing leasing department, I conceptualized, designed and developed a leasing packet for an affordable housing development in the Central District called the Liberty Bank Building.', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '160-autosave-v1', '', '', '2018-07-24 22:02:56', '2018-07-24 22:02:56', '', 160, 'http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/160-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(167, 1, '2018-07-07 02:57:30', '2018-07-07 02:57:30', 'For the Capitol Hill Housing leasing department, I conceptualized, designed and developed a leasing packet for an affordable housing development in the Central District called the Liberty Bank Building. The building is a multi-use apartment complex with entirely low-income eligible units and over 2,500 square feet of commercial space for local businesses. It is currently under construction and set to open in February 2019.\r\n<h3>Background</h3>\r\nThe Liberty Bank Building is the result of a collective partnership between Africa Town Central District, Byrd Barr Place, Black Community Impact Alliance, the Capitol HIll Housing Foundation, local community leaders and founders of the Liberty Bank. This historic project aspires to preserve the legacy of the first black-owned bank west of the Mississippi by continuing to support the community for years to come. We wanted to highlight this legacy, preserve the existing identity of the Central District, and steward in a new generation of community engagement.\r\n<h3>Project Challenges &amp; Goals</h3>\r\nHistorically, the Seattle City government divested from the Central District. This segregated community became a hub for pan African and migrant community culture. Today it is experiencing rapid urban development. As rent increases faster than the existing community members are able to afford, they become displaced from their homes. The Liberty Bank Bank building will provide affordable housing for these very residents, in a continued effort to preserve the Central District’s cultural identity.\r\n\r\nCapitol Hill Housing provided me a single microsoft word document with all existing information about the leasing process for the Liberty Bank Building. It contained complex language, had a lengthy format, and was largely inaccessible to individuals most in need of this very information. Consequently the inaccessibility of this information led to rumors being spread about the project development and its leasing process.\r\n\r\nThe leasing packet design was heavily influenced by all these factors. The scoped project goals were:\r\nto clarify the eligibility requirements for affordable housing,\r\nwalk applicants through the leasing process and timeline for the Liberty Bank Building,\r\nand affirmatively market to audiences affected by rapid urbanization in the Central District.\r\n<h3>Design Strategy</h3>\r\nA major variable for the The Liberty Bank Building leasing packet is the differing audience segments I needed to tailor the design to. The primary audience is individuals and families living in the Central District who qualify for affordable housing and those looking for information on the leasing process and how to apply for the Liberty Bank Building. The secondary audience is community members and small businesses, particularly of pan-African decent, affected by displacement in the Central District; or those individuals and community partners at risk of being unable to afford rapid rent increases in the housing and commercial real estate market.\r\n\r\nIn order to clarify the eligibility requirements for affordable housing and walk applicants through the leasing process, I neatly organized complex leasing information in a format accessible to a broad audience whom are largely unfamiliar with affordable housing regulation in Seattle.\r\n\r\nThe Liberty Bank Building partners will utilize the leasing packet to affirmatively market to audiences affected by rapid urbanization by hosting local community events in which these leasing packets will be distributed to local residents. We intend partnered staff to be present, answering questions on site. The visual design compliments their marketing tactics in a way that communicates the history of the Liberty Bank, expresses the future tone of the Liberty Bank Building, and un-offensively appreciates and respects the pan-african community in the Central District.\r\n<h3>Design Solution</h3>\r\n[scroller] LBB Leasing Packet Slideshow [/scroller]\r\n\r\nThe Capitol Hill Housing Foundation hired me to deliver a single leasing packet of the following items:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>General building information like amenities, photos, and location map</li>\r\n 	<li>Affordable housing process overview</li>\r\n 	<li>Income requirements for applying</li>\r\n 	<li>A timeline of the project development and leasing</li>\r\n 	<li>Frequently Asked Questions</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Design Process</h3>\r\nLeasing affordable housing differs from non-subsidized apartments; and the Liberty Bank Building itself poses a unique application process. While focusing on conceptual development with moodboards, typography and color schemes, I worked with the partners team to effortlessly to categorize, synthesize and tailored content strategically.\r\n\r\nThe visual design is intuitive and simply explains affordable housing, the application process, and eligibility requirements using accessible language. Visual graphs and tables help applicants interactively determine their eligibility, while a four step visual breakdown walks them through the leasing process. We sourced historic photos from the Liberty Bank partners, and composed them with photos of the new Liberty Bank Building. We even coordinated with the architect to render a more diverse group of people in the building renderings. I was sure to prioritize contact information; and in case anyone has additional questions, a subsequent spread contains Frequently Ask Questions. I also included a handy timeline of key dates for the project construction and leasing process.\r\n<h3>Project Impact</h3>\r\nThe layout itself is a huge improvement from the single word document the partners began with. Including photos of the historic Central District and current community events, drastically improved the packets relatability to our target audience. The use of visual motifs, typographic hierarchy and layout, and brand consistency were driving forces behind achieving project goals.\r\n\r\nThe Capitol Hill Housing Association ensures their approach to each community building is both intentional and affective in targeting individuals in need of affordable housing. Upon beginning this assignment, there were minor tensions rising between community partners as its construction progressed. The success of this collateral project strengthened the Liberty Bank Building partners’ trust in Capitol Hill Housings’ ability to be aware of its context and deliver content that is relevant to this project’s audience.\r\n\r\nThe a vast majority of the partners responded very positively to the leasing packet design, with only minor tweaks to the cover needed after the fact. Overall the project delivered on schedule and within the partners budget. Once the Liberty Bank Building partners begin actively marketing, it is anticipated this leasing packet will allow local community members to become more familiar with the affordable housing application process and give them the confidence to inquire about living at the Liberty Bank Building.\r\n<h3>Sources</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><a href="http://libertybankbuilding.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Liberty Bank Building</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href="http://www.africatownlandtrust.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Africa Town Land Trust, Central District</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href="https://byrdbarrplace.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Byrd Barr Place</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href="http://david-harris-wkj7.squarespace.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Black Community Impact Alliance</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href="https://www.capitolhillhousing.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Capitol Hill Housing Foundation</a></li>\r\n</ul>', 'The Liberty Bank Building', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '160-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-07-07 02:57:30', '2018-07-07 02:57:30', '', 160, 'http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/160-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(168, 1, '2018-07-07 03:07:37', '2018-07-07 03:07:37', 'Capitol Hill Housing (CHH) is a public corporation organized by the City of Seattle. Their mission is to build vibrant and engaged communities through affordable housing and community development. In total, CHH manages approximately 50 properties, each with eligibility requirements ranging from low-income, elderly, disabled, veteran and other eligibility restricted units.\r\n<h3>Background</h3>\r\nCapitol Hill Housing Resident Service department employs Resident Service Coordinators (RSC) to inform, coordinate and provide resources to its diverse residents. The RSC primarily communicate with residents through information sheets, advertisements on community boards, door-to-door tactics, community and building events and direct one-on-one contact. They serve as the central resource for all residents living in CHH properties, providing a range of services including general questions, hosting community events and coordinating need-based services such as rental assistance, live-in health care and transportation services to name a few.\r\n<h3>Project Challenges &amp; Goals</h3>\r\nAccording to CHH resident surveys, less than half the residents were aware that CHH provided individualized support through its Resident Services Program. Additionally, the RSC relied heavily of Microsoft word, so it became paramount to create a template system any RSC could use on any type of computer. As such, the project goals were identified as follows:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Inform residents about RSC and increase awareness of the many services available</li>\r\n 	<li>Simplify the layout and be consistent with the CHH brand</li>\r\n 	<li>Improve the collateral functionality and usability for RSC</li>\r\n 	<li>Improve and increase the visual accessibility for CHH’s diverse residents</li>\r\n 	<li>Improve and increase the trust between resident and RSC in individual communities</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Design Strategy</h3>\r\nTo achieve the stated goals, I set about the process of brainstorming the visual design, assessing technical concerns, researching the methods in which RSC communicate with residents and the reviewing the overall brand image and messaging of CHH. To increase overall brand awareness, I set forth to unify the CHH brand image and develop a template system that could be unique for individual properties, yet consistent with the larger CHH brand. Additionally, I created pieces that were simply formatted, easily customizable and implementable by the RSC in each residential community.\r\n<h3>Design Solutions</h3>\r\nThe client hired me to provide graphic design services for five collateral items most utilized by the RSC. The pieces were to be redesigned, while meeting the aforementioned goals in to the five unified, brand consistent templates:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Building Welcome Sheets</li>\r\n 	<li>RSC Persona Sheets</li>\r\n 	<li>Monthly Events Calendar</li>\r\n 	<li>Event Flyers</li>\r\n 	<li>Resource One Sheets</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n[image_block]<img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-49" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE_Resident-Services-poster_11x17-663x1024.jpg" alt="" />\r\n<h4>Resident Services Poster</h4>\r\nIn addition to the five collateral templates, I designed a large format poster to advertise CHH Resident Services. It primarily informs residents of the services available to them. We proposed to mount these posters on community boards in public building spaces, around the building property and within CHH offices. This poster design acts as the outward, public facing representation of the CHH Resident Services available.\r\n[/image_block]\r\n\r\n[image_block][scroller]<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-51" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE_welcome-sheetgeneral_8.5x11.jpg" alt="" /><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-52" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE_welcome-sheetJoeyG_8.5x11.jpg" alt="" /><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-34" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/tmpl_individual-rsc-768x1024.jpg" alt="" /><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-32" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/poster_resident-services-e1530318746544-834x1024.jpg" alt="" />[/scroller]\r\n<h4>Building Welcome and RSC Persona Sheets</h4>\r\nUpon move in, residents receive a packet which includes the building welcome and RSC persona sheets. The building welcome sheet informs residents about CHH and resources available through the Resident Services program. The RSC persona sheet introduces the specific RS Coordinator supporting the residents’ property. Both these documents are intended to welcome residents and provide them essential resources, contact information, and other important details about CHH and RSC.[/image_block]\r\n\r\n[image_block][scroller]<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-53" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE-calendar_11x8.5.jpg" alt="" /> <img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-35" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/tmpl_residence-calendar-e1530319018147-1024x803.jpg" alt="" />[/scroller]\r\n<h4>Monthly Events Calendar</h4>\r\nMonthly calendars specific to each property highlight upcoming community events. They are available online, by email and posted in community spaces. After creating a 2018-19 monthly calendar template with updated styles, I added additional content to the footer, specific to each RSC and building property. This allows the RSC to put their contact information and specific building information on the calendars for residents to easily reference.\r\n[/image_block]\r\n\r\n[image_block][scroller]<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-48" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE_event-poster_8.5x11.jpg" alt="" /> <img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-47" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/BLANK_event-flyer_x2_5.5x8.5-1024x791.jpg" alt="" /> <img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-33" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/tmpl_event-flyers-e1530319332673-797x1024.jpg" alt="" />[/scroller]\r\n<h4>Event Flyers</h4>\r\nEvent flyers are posted in community spaces to advertise a variety of events and workshops. For maximum ease of use and flexibility, I designed a variable sidebar layout for things like recurrent event dates and event sign-ups. RSCs can choose between having a single event date or multiple recurring events. Additionally, there is an option for a sign-up content block with a variable height, allowing for maximum customization. I also created a half-sheet event template that reduces event information to its hook, a primary message and call to action, for use by the RSC as handouts for local, building specific events.\r\n[/image_block]\r\n\r\n[image_block][scroller]<img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-50" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE_resource-one-sheet_8.5x11-791x1024.jpg" alt="" /> <img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-36" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/tmpl_resource-one-sheet-e1530319531779-819x1024.jpg" alt="" />[/scroller]\r\n<h4>Resource One Sheets</h4>\r\nOne sheets are a template that list all relevant contact information for each resource category. I created a typographic system and grid layout that adapts to each collateral template. The system I conceived maintains the appropriate balance between text legibility and readability. This one sheet example is the simplest form of typography and grid layout utilized across every template.\r\n[/image_block]\r\n\r\n<h3>Design Process</h3>\r\nIn developing the collateral pieces, the challenges and goals of the client were kept in the forefront. As such, in all steps of the project development the following were considered: awareness and consistency; accessibility; and usability.\r\n\r\n<h4>Awareness &amp; Consistency</h4>\r\nConsistency affects people’s awareness and trust of a brand. If residents aren’t clear what the RSC provide and who they are in relation to CHH, then they are likely to have less faith in the services provided. I directly addressed this issue through a systematically implemented visual design. Through use of typography, white space, graphic elements and color, I achieved overall visual consistency between each collateral template.\r\n\r\n<h4>Accessibility</h4>\r\nThe visual design compliments the content strategy and does not detract from it. We simplified the text and used language understood by a general audience. I also utilized a relatively large font size to improve legibility for residents with visual impairments. Attention was also paid to color usage, to increase accessibility for color visually impaired people.\r\n\r\n<h4>Usability</h4>\r\nTo provide maximum ease of use for the RSC, who may not have a background in design or layout programs, I chose Adobe InDesign to make the templates. The Adobe InDesign has excellent interface with Adobe Acrobat, the program used by the majority of CHH employees. This has resulted in great ease of use for the RSC, allowing for editable content while maintaining overall brand consistency and increased design awareness.\r\n\r\n<h3>Project Results</h3>\r\nThe overall response from the Client, CHH employees, Resident Service Coordinators and residents was overwhelming positive. The visual design and functionality of my project deliverables exceeded their expectations. In fact, after using the new templates, several RSC requested more variations for the event flyers, resulting in additional project work. In recreating these design pieces for CHH, I created a visual design similar enough to the existing look to maintain the familiarity of the old styles, while drastically improving brand accessibility, functionality, consistency and awareness. Our focus on content strategy, language and visual harmony allowed the simple style to accommodate the diverse audiences with propriety and appeal.\r\n\r\n[scroller]<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-71" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/IMG_3094_small.jpg" alt="Capitol Hill Housing community event" /> <img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-90" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/IMG_2666-768x1024.jpg" alt="" /> <img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-89" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/IMG_2499-1024x768.jpg" alt="" /> <img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-70" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CAPHILLHOUSING-186-1-1024x683.jpg" alt="Ashwin Warrior enters the Capitol Hill Housing offices on 12th Ave." />[/scroller]', 'Capitol Hill Housing Resident Services', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '23-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-07-07 03:07:37', '2018-07-07 03:07:37', '', 23, 'http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/23-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
