design is intuitive and simply explains affordable housing, the application process, and eligibility requirements using accessible language. Visual graphs and tables help applicants interactively determine their eligibility, while a four step visual breakdown walks them through the leasing process. We sourced historic photos from the Liberty Bank partners, and composed them with photos of the new Liberty Bank Building. We even coordinated with the architect to render a more diverse group of people in the building renderings. I was sure to prioritize contact information; and in case anyone has additional questions, a subsequent spread contains Frequently Ask Questions. I also included a handy timeline of key dates for the project construction and leasing process.\r\n<h3>Project Impact</h3>\r\nThe layout itself is a huge improvement from the single word document the partners began with. Including photos of the historic Central District and current community events, drastically improved the packets relatability to our target audience. The use of visual motifs, typographic hierarchy and layout, and brand consistency were driving forces behind achieving project goals.\r\n\r\nThe Capitol Hill Housing Association ensures their approach to each community building is both intentional and affective in targeting individuals in need of affordable housing. Upon beginning this assignment, there were minor tensions rising between community partners as its construction progressed. The success of this collateral project strengthened the Liberty Bank Building partners’ trust in Capitol Hill Housings’ ability to be aware of its context and deliver content that is relevant to this project’s audience.\r\n\r\nThe a vast majority of the partners responded very positively to the leasing packet design, with only minor tweaks to the cover needed after the fact. Overall the project delivered on schedule and within the partners budget. Once the Liberty Bank Building partners begin actively marketing, it is anticipated this leasing packet will allow local community members to become more familiar with the affordable housing application process and give them the confidence to inquire about living at the Liberty Bank Building.\r\n<h3>Sources</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><a href="http://libertybankbuilding.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Liberty Bank Building</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href="http://www.africatownlandtrust.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Africa Town Land Trust, Central District</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href="https://byrdbarrplace.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Byrd Barr Place</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href="http://david-harris-wkj7.squarespace.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Black Community Impact Alliance</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href="https://www.capitolhillhousing.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Capitol Hill Housing Foundation</a></li>\r\n</ul>', 'The Liberty Bank Building', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '160-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-07-07 03:52:38', '2018-07-07 03:52:38', '', 160, 'http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/160-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(183, 1, '2017-02-11 12:00:21', '2017-02-11 12:00:21', '<h3>Background</h3>I was one of three freelance designers retained by local restaurant owner Kevin Chung to develop brand identity and menu signage for his new restaurant Cheese Meats Bread (CMB) in 2017. The project scope included developing a logo design, brand style-guide, handout menu, large format menu, and food packaging for CMB\'s grand opening.\n<h3>Project Challenges &amp; Goals</h3>Cheese Meats Bread is an international take on an American classic—the grilled cheese sandwich. Mr. Chung planned to open in the Uwajimaya Village marketplace in the International District, Seattle\n<h3>Design Strategy</h3>During the research phase we talked largely about how to add an international flare to an American classic without having the brand be offensive or too intrusive for a largely international audience.\n<h3>Design Solution</h3>Our team worked collaboratively throughout the project brainstorming, concept development, and refinement phases. When executing the final deliverables, my teammate created the typographic pattern and packaging design, while I focused on the large format menu board, small take-out menu, and brand identity style guide.\n\n[image_block][scroller]<img src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CMB_style-guide_8.5x11.jpg" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-185" alt=""><img src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CMB-menu_6x11.jpg" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-188" alt=""><img src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CMB_menu-board_6x4ft_opt-2.jpg" class="alignnone wp-image-187 size-full" alt="">[/scroller]\n<h4>Brand style guide</h4>\n<h4>6x11 in. takeout menu</h4>\n<h4>6x4 ft. menu board</h4>[/image_block]\n<h3>Design Process</h3>While brainstorming and exploring concepts, we provided the client with numerous concepts, each of which approached the CMB brand from a unique lens. Upon listening more closely to general feedback from others and the client’s reaction to our presentation, they liked the variety of font selections we provided, but overall they gravitated towards more simpler fonts and cleaner illustrations. We decided on a typographic solution that used a simple logo mark and a typographic pattern as the primary brand elements, with a gooey yellow accent color—<em>Yumm!</em>\n<h3>Project Impact</h3>We successfully delivered the brand identity packet to the client on schedule and within our budget. Afterwards, I maintained a positive relationship with the client and both design colleagues. CMB is open today and thriving in Seattle’s International District at the Uwajimaya Village market place.\n\n<img src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/IMG_1633.jpg" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-344" alt="">\n<h3>Sources</h3>\n<ul>\n 	<li><a href="https://cheesemeatsbread.life/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Cheese Meats Bread</a></li>\n 	<li><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/chriselvis/">Client Relations: Chris Mercurio</a></li>\n 	<li><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/kenzie-nicholson/">Designer: Kenzie Nicholson</a></li>\n</ul>', 'Cheese Meats Bread', 'The locally successful restaurant owner Kevin Chung, retained me to design a brand identity and menu signage for his new restaurant Cheese Meats Bread (CMB) in 2017.', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'cheese-meats-bread', '', '', '2018-07-25 19:38:35', '2018-07-25 19:38:35', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/?p=183', 0, 'post', '', 0),
