(217, 1, '2016-03-10 12:00:42', '2016-03-10 12:00:42', '<h3>Background</h3>\r\nFor a service learning assignment, I formed a design team with several colleagues and we partnered with the Capitol Hill Arts District (CHAD) to design an awareness campaign that coincided with their new website.\r\n<h3>Project Challenges &amp; Goals</h3>\r\nAccording to a neighborhood survey, many residents were unaware that CHAD existed. It was the first neighborhood to be named as part of the Arts &amp; Cultural Districts program by the Seattle City Government in 2014. CHAD launched their website in 2017 to elevate its presence.\r\n\r\nMy team’s primary goal was to build off the visual tone established on their website and to increase community awareness. Another key challenge for this assignment was to manage, plan, and coordinate a collaborative design with a team. As the Design Lead, I worked closely with the team to delegate and deliver a comprehensive collateral design and marketing plan to our client.\r\n<h3>Design Strategy</h3>\r\nOur team developed a targeted marketing campaign, focusing on the environmental and neighborhood aspects of CHAD. By designing the collateral materials as elements of a wayfinding system and complimenting pre-existing brand elements, we increased pedestrian and drivers’ perception of CHAD’s physical boundary.\r\n\r\nInside of the CHAD, we empowered community partners to facilitate the neighborhood brand. We distributed small format postcards and stickers to community partners and asked them to display and sell them within their business. Digital assets, like neighborhood photographs and Facebook cover photos, expanded the CHAD presence online. Additionally, the hashtags #NowEntering and #CapitolHillArtsDistrict were applied to the collateral to track the conversation online.\r\n<h3>Design Solution</h3>\r\nThe Capitol Hill Arts District requested that we deliver each of the following:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>11x17 in. poster design</li>\r\n 	<li>6x4 in. postcard design</li>\r\n 	<li>4x4 in. round sticker</li>\r\n 	<li>Facebook cover photo</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[scroller bg-color="white"]\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-224" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_poster-mockup-side-by-side.jpg" alt="" /><img class="alignnone wp-image-225 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_poster-telephone-pole-01.jpg" alt="" /><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-226" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_poster-telephone-pole-02.jpg" alt="" />[/scroller]\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-220 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/Capitol-Hill-Arts-District-social-media-mockup.jpg" alt="" />\r\n<h3>Design Process</h3>\r\nAs the Team Lead, it was my responsibility to understand the scope of work, coordinate a schedule between the designers and our client, delegate tasks to each team member, and maintain a positive focus on the project goals and deliverables.\r\n\r\nThe design process included reviewing existing collateral and advertisements, and brainstorming ways to expand upon the existing wayfinding signage. Utilizing over 50 photos of public artworks and murals within the Arts district, our team developed initial concepts, developed content and produced a series of layouts.\r\n\r\nThe project scope also included researching of local printers and advertisement companies, coordinating and securing price estimates for printing and posting flyers around Capitol Hill.\r\n<h3>Project Impact</h3>\r\nOur team presented the campaign to the Arts District Steering Committee and recommended a course of action for marketing CHAD. The committee response was overwhelmingly positive.\r\n\r\nThey appreciated the versatility of the design system we made. The text content was minimal and remained consistent across the collateral. The CHAD logo was prominently featured, while the interchangeable background photos of CHAD murals highlighted the local community. The interchangeable backgrounds empowered the committee to swap out photographs with other options—sourcing background photos from district partners and community members delivered more community value. This unique, adaptable design approach proved very successful to the client.\r\n\r\nThe marketing collateral served as advertisements and aided wayfinding. The large format posters were put along the perimeter of the district to identify its boundary, while personal collateral items were used inside partner locations. The collateral did a solid job notifying people they were entering a new city neighborhood and complemented existing CHAD brand signage. The content was focused and clearly promoted shared art and cultural values, which improved people’s awareness and perception of CHAD.\r\n\r\nTo our excitement, many businesses endorsed our efforts to market the CHAD. They liked having the responsibility as a community partner to facilitate the neighborhood’s brand. Some community partners even opted to put the poster advertisement in their window.\r\n\r\nThe committee accepted our proposed marketing plan and the posters, stickers, and postcards were successfully promoted in the Capitol Hill Arts District throughout the summer of 2017.\r\n<h3>Sources</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><a href="http://capitolhillarts.org/now-entering/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Capitol Hill Arts, Now Entering campaign page</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href="https://segd.org/what-wayfinding/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">What is Wayfinding? — Seattle Environmental Graphic Design</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[column_wrap count="2"]\r\n\r\n[column]\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-223 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_postcards-front-01.jpg" alt="" />\r\n[/column]\r\n\r\n[column]\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-222 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_postcards-back.jpg" alt="" width="2812" height="2824" />\r\n\r\n[/column]\r\n\r\n[/column_wrap]\r\n\r\n[column_wrap count="9"]\r\n[column]\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-234 size-thumbnail" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-dark-150x150.jpg" alt="" width="150" height="150" />\r\n[/column][column]\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-227 size-thumbnail" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-1-red-150x150.jpg" alt="" width="135" height="135" />\r\n[/column][column]\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-228 size-thumbnail" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-2-orange-150x150.jpg" alt="" width="135" height="135" />\r\n[/column][column]\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-229 size-thumbnail" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-3-yellow-150x150.jpg" alt="" width="135" height="135" />\r\n[/column][column]\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-230 size-thumbnail" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-4-green-150x150.jpg" alt="" width="135" height="135" />\r\n[/column][column]\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-231 size-thumbnail" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-5-teal-150x150.jpg" alt="" width="150" height="150" />\r\n[/column][column]\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-232 size-thumbnail" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-6-blue-150x150.jpg" alt="" width="135" height="135" />\r\n[/column][column]\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-233 size-thumbnail" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-7-purple-150x150.jpg" alt="" width="135" height="135" />\r\n[/column][column]\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-235 size-thumbnail" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-light-150x150.jpg" alt="" width="135" height="135" />\r\n[/column]\r\n[/column_wrap]', 'Capitol Hill Arts District', 'As Design Team Lead, some colleagues and I partnered with the Capitol Hill Arts District to design an awareness campaign that coincided with their new website.', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'capitol-hill-arts-district', '', '\nhttp://capitolhillarts.org/now-entering/', '2018-07-25 19:40:45', '2018-07-25 19:40:45', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/?p=217', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(218, 1, '2018-07-07 05:11:42', '2018-07-07 05:11:42', 'For a service learning assignment, I formed a design team with design colleagues, Alicia Smith and Ivy Ye. We partnered with the Capitol Hill Arts District (CH Arts District) to design an awareness campaign to coincide with their new website launch.\r\n<h3>Project Challenges &amp; Goals</h3>\r\nAccording to a recent neighborhood serve, many residents are unaware that Capitol Hill was the first district to be named as part of the Arts &amp; Cultural Districts program by the Seattle City Government (2014). After a couple years of partnering and community building, CH Arts District launched their new website in 2017 to elevate its presence. This print marketing campaign built off the visual tone established on their website and the primary goal was to increase local community’s awareness of the CH Arts District.\r\n\r\nA key challenge for this design assignment was to manage, plan, and coordinate a collaborative design with a team. As the Design Team Lead, I worked closely with Alicia and Ivy to delegate and deliver to our client a comprehensive collateral design and marketing plan.\r\n<h3>Design Strategy</h3>\r\nOur team collaboratively wrote and developed an original marketing campaign. We focused on the environmental and neighborhood aspect of the CH Arts District by designing the marketing collateral as elements of a wayfinding system (link) to compliment pre-existing brand elements. For example, they recently installed new road signs on the CH Arts District perimeter that now include the logo. This improved drivers’ awareness of the Arts District brand and geographic location. We wanted to capitalize on their approach to expand the wayfinding signage for pedestrians and increase people’s perception of the CH Arts District physical boundary.\r\n\r\nInside of the CH Arts District, we empowered community partners to facilitate the neighborhood brand. We distributed small format postcards and stickers to community partners and asked them to display and or sell them within their business.\r\n\r\nDigital assets, like neighborhood photographs and Facebook cover photos, expanded the CH Arts District presence online. Additionally, the hashtags #NowEntering and #CapitolHillArtsDistrict were applied to the collateral to track the conversation online.\r\n<h3>Design Solution</h3>\r\nThe Capitol Hill Arts District requested that we deliver to them each the following:\r\n\r\n11x17 in. poster design\r\n\r\n6x4 in. postcard design\r\n\r\n4x4 in. round sticker\r\n\r\nFacebook cover photo\r\n<h3>Design Process</h3>\r\nAs the Design Team Lead, it was my responsibility to understand the scope of work to be done, coordinate a schedule between the designers and our client, delegate tasks to each team member, and maintain a positive focus on the project goals and deliverables.\r\n\r\nFirst, we got together and brainstormed the idea to use the collateral advertisements to expand the CH Arts District wayfinding signage. One weekend, I spent the day walking around Capitol Hill and captured over 50 photos of public artworks and murals within the Arts District perimeter. Then, our team regrouped and critiqued initial sketches and define our concept more.\r\n\r\nWith the community photographs to use as the background content for the postcard and poster, Alicia and I produced a series of poster layouts; while Ivy designed the stickers. Alicia went ahead and made the postcard layout. I used the photographs to create social media cover photos. Once again, we regrouped and critiqued our team concept, before further refining the details and presenting to the client.\r\n\r\nAfter the final designs were selected by the client, I thoroughly researched local printers and advertisement companies in Capitol Hill to coordinate getting price estimates, printing the collateral, and posting the flyers. I then put everything together into a single presentation the give to the Arts District Steering Committee.\r\n<h3>Project Impact</h3>\r\nIn March 2017, our team presented the campaign to the Arts District Steering Committee during one of their weekly meetings and recommended a course of action for marketing the CH Arts District.\r\n\r\nThe committee response was overwhelmingly positive. They appreciate the versatility of the design system we made. The text content was minimal and remained consistent across the collateral. The CH Arts District logo was prominently feature like they requested, while the interchangeable background photos of CH Arts District murals highlighted the local community.\r\n\r\nThis design system delivered more value because, since the background content is interchangeable, it empowered the committee to swap out photographs with other options we provided, or even to source background photos from district partners and community members. This was a unique approach to the steering committee and they appreciated the adaptability we provided them.\r\n\r\nThe marketing collateral served as advertisements and aided wayfinding. The large format posters were put along the perimeter of the district to identify its boundary, while small collateral items were used inside partner buildings to allow them to associate with the Arts District. The collateral did a solid job notifying people they were entering a new city neighborhood and complemented existing CH Arts District brand signage. The content was focused and clearly promoted shared art and cultural values, which improved people\'s awareness and perception of the CH Arts District.\r\n\r\nOne issue was, the advertisements were posting these on street poles and our design had to compete with local musicians and community event posters. We combated this issue by reducing the text content to its primary elements and adding ample emphasis to the header. The variety of background photos, taken from the local community, gave the poster design a sense of familiarity because much of the featured artwork was iconic for the Capitol Hill Arts District Community.\r\n\r\nIn combination with branded stickers and postcards, we anticipated that residents would interact with CH Arts District collateral as they enter the neighborhood perimeter, then within community partner locations, and begin to associate the partner location with the CH Arts District.\r\n\r\nTo our excitement, many businesses endorsed our efforts to market the CH Arts District. They liked having the responsibility as a community partners to facilitate the neighborhood’s brand and promote community art engagement. Some community partners even opted to put the poster advertisement in their window, too. After all the CH Arts District would not exist if it were not for the nearly 50 neighborhood partners who make up the Capitol Hill Arts District.\r\n\r\nThe committee accepted our proposed marketing plan and the posters, stickers, and postcards were successfully promoted in the Capitol Hill Arts District throughout the summer of 2017.\r\n<h3>Sources</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><a href="http://capitolhillarts.org/now-entering/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Capitol Hill Arts, Now Entering campaign</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a style="font-family: -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, \'Segoe UI\', Roboto, Oxygen-Sans, Ubuntu, Cantarell, \'Helvetica Neue\', sans-serif;" href="https://segd.org/what-wayfinding" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Seattle Environmental Graphic Design: What is Wayfinding?</a></li>\r\n</ul>', 'Capitol Hill Arts District', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '217-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-07-07 05:11:42', '2018-07-07 05:11:42', '', 217, 'http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/217-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ;
