(262, 1, '2018-07-09 17:57:59', '2018-07-09 17:57:59', '<h3>Background</h3>\r\nFor a service learning assignment, I formed a design team with colleagues, Alicia Smith and Ivy Ye. We partnered with the Capitol Hill Arts District (CH Arts District) to design an awareness campaign to coincide with their new website launch.\r\n<h3>Project Challenges &amp; Goals</h3>\r\nAccording to a recent neighborhood survey, the majority of residents were unaware that Capitol Hill Arts District even exists. It was the first neighborhood to be named as part of the Arts &amp; Cultural Districts program by the Seattle City Government (2014). CH Arts District launched their new website in 2017 to elevate its presence. My team’s primary goal was to build off the visual tone established on their website and to increase local community’s awareness of the CH Arts District.\r\n\r\nAnother key challenge for this design assignment was to manage, plan, and coordinate a collaborative design with a team. As the Design Team Lead, I worked closely with Alicia and Ivy to delegate and deliver to our client a comprehensive collateral design and marketing plan.\r\n<h3>Design Strategy</h3>\r\nOur team collaboratively wrote and developed an original marketing campaign. We focused on the environmental and neighborhood aspect of the CH Arts District by designing the marketing collateral as elements of a wayfinding system to compliment pre-existing brand elements. For example, CH Arts District recently installed new road signs that include their logo on the District perimeter. This improved drivers’ awareness of the Arts District brand and geographic location. We capitalize on their approach buy advertising the large format posters along the perimeter. This expanded the wayfinding signage for pedestrians and increase people’s perception of the CH Arts District physical boundary.\r\n\r\nInside of the CH Arts District, we empowered community partners to facilitate the neighborhood brand. We distributed small format postcards and stickers to community partners and asked them to display and sell them within their business.\r\n\r\nDigital assets, like neighborhood photographs and Facebook cover photos, expanded the CH Arts District presence online. Additionally, the hashtags #NowEntering and #CapitolHillArtsDistrict were applied to the collateral to track the conversation online.\r\n<h3>Design Solution</h3>\r\nThe Capitol Hill Arts District requested that we deliver to them each the following:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>11x17 in. poster design</li>\r\n 	<li>6x4 in. postcard design</li>\r\n 	<li>4x4 in. round sticker</li>\r\n 	<li>Facebook cover photo</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[scroller bg-color="white"]<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-224" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_poster-mockup-side-by-side.jpg" alt="" /><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-225" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_poster-telephone-pole-01.jpg" alt="" /><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-226" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_poster-telephone-pole-02.jpg" alt="" />[/scroller]\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-220" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/Capitol-Hill-Arts-District-social-media-mockup.jpg" alt="" />\r\n<h3>Design Process</h3>\r\nAs the Design Team Lead, it was my responsibility to understand the scope of work to be done, coordinate a schedule between the designers and our client, delegate tasks to each team member, and maintain a positive focus on the project goals and deliverables.\r\n\r\nThe design process included reviewing existing collateral and advertisements and brainstorming on ways to expand up on existing wayfinding signage. Utilizing over 50 photos of public artworks and murals within the Arts district, our team developed initial sketches and defined our concept. Next we developed the postcard and poster content and produced a series of layouts and sticker designs. The photographs were also used to create social media cover photos. Refined concepts were present to the client for final design and approval. The project scope also included researching of local printers and advertisement companies, coordinating and securing price estimates, printing the collateral and posting the flyer and presenting to the Arts District Steering Committee following final design approval from client.\r\n<h3>Project Impact</h3>\r\nOur team presented the campaign to the Arts District Steering Committee and recommended a course of action for marketing the CH Arts District.\r\n\r\nThe committee response was overwhelmingly positive. They appreciate the versatility of the design system we made. The text content was minimal and remained consistent across the collateral. The CH Arts District logo was prominently feature like they requested, while the interchangeable background photos of CH Arts District murals highlighted the local community. The interchangeable backgrounds empowered the committee to swap out photographs with other options we provided. We even proposed to source background photos from district partners and community members to delivered more community value. This was a unique approach to the and CH Arts District committee appreciated the variety and adaptability we provided them.\r\n\r\nThe marketing collateral served as advertisements and aided wayfinding. The large format posters were put along the perimeter of the district to identify its boundary, while small collateral items were used inside partner buildings to allow them to associate with the Arts District. The collateral did a solid job notifying people they were entering a new city neighborhood and complemented existing CH Arts District brand signage. The content was focused and clearly promoted shared art and cultural values, which improved people\'s awareness and perception of the CH Arts District.\r\n\r\nIn combination with branded stickers and postcards, we anticipated that residents would interact with CH Arts District collateral as they enter the neighborhood perimeter, then within community partner locations, and begin to associate the partner location with the CH Arts District. By diversifying our advertisements and the locations we marketed, it allowed more audience touch points to increase its impact.\r\n\r\nTo our excitement, many businesses endorsed our efforts to market the CH Arts District. They liked having the responsibility as a community partner to facilitate the neighborhood’s brand. Some community partners even opted to put the poster advertisement in their window.\r\n\r\nThe committee accepted our proposed marketing plan and the posters, stickers, and postcards were successfully promoted in the Capitol Hill Arts District throughout the summer of 2017.\r\n<h3>Sources</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><a href="http://capitolhillarts.org/now-entering/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Capitol Hill Arts, Now Entering campaign page</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href="https://segd.org/what-wayfinding/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">What is Wayfinding? — Seattle Environmental Graphic Design</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[column_wrap count="2"]\r\n\r\n[column]\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-223" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_postcards-front-01.jpg" alt="" />\r\n[/column]\r\n\r\n[column]\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-222 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_postcards-back.jpg" alt="" width="2812" height="2824" />\r\n\r\n[/column]\r\n\r\n[/column_wrap]\r\n\r\n[column_wrap count="9"]\r\n[column]\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-234 size-thumbnail" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-dark-150x150.jpg" alt="" width="150" height="150" />\r\n[/column][column]\r\n<img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-227 alignnone" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-1-red-150x150.jpg" alt="" />\r\n[/column][column]\r\n<img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-228 alignnone" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-2-orange-150x150.jpg" alt="" />\r\n[/column][column]\r\n<img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-229 alignnone" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-3-yellow-150x150.jpg" alt="" />\r\n[/column][column]\r\n<img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-230 alignnone" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-4-green-150x150.jpg" alt="" />\r\n[/column][column]\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-231 size-thumbnail" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-5-teal-150x150.jpg" alt="" width="150" height="150" />\r\n[/column][column]\r\n<img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-232 alignnone" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-6-blue-150x150.jpg" alt="" />\r\n[/column][column]\r\n<img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-233 alignnone" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-7-purple-150x150.jpg" alt="" />\r\n[/column][column]\r\n<img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-235 alignnone" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-light-150x150.jpg" alt="" />\r\n[/column]\r\n[/column_wrap]', 'Capitol Hill Arts District', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '217-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-07-09 17:57:59', '2018-07-09 17:57:59', '', 217, 'http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/217-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(263, 1, '2018-07-09 18:05:23', '2018-07-09 18:05:23', 'For the Capitol Hill Housing leasing department, I conceptualized, designed and developed a leasing packet for an affordable housing development in the Central District called the Liberty Bank Building. The building is a multi-use apartment complex with entirely low-income eligible units and over 2,500 square feet of commercial space for local businesses. It is currently under construction and set to open in February 2019.\r\n<h3>Background</h3>\r\nThe Liberty Bank Building is the result of a collective partnership between Africa Town Central District, Byrd Barr Place, Black Community Impact Alliance, the Capitol HIll Housing Foundation, local community leaders and founders of the Liberty Bank. This historic project aspires to preserve the legacy of the first black-owned bank in the western United States by continuing to support the community for years to come. We wanted to highlight this legacy, preserve the existing identity of the Central District, and steward in a new generation of community engagement.\r\n<h3>Project Challenges &amp; Goals</h3>\r\nHistorically, the Seattle City government divested from the Central District. This segregated community became a hub for pan-African and migrant community culture. Today it is experiencing rapid urban development. As rent increases faster than the existing community members are able to afford, they become displaced from their homes. The Liberty Bank Bank building will provide affordable housing for these very residents, in a continued effort to preserve the Central District’s cultural identity.\r\n\r\nExisting Liberty Bank material, while resourceful, was lengthy and complex, making it impractical for the target audience. A key assignment for this project was creating leasing content that would be understandable and usable for all members of the community.\r\n\r\nThe leasing packet design was heavily influenced by all these factors. The project goals were:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>to clarify the eligibility requirements for affordable housing</li>\r\n 	<li>walk applicants through the leasing process and timeline for the Liberty Bank Building</li>\r\n 	<li>affirmatively market to audiences affected by rapid urbanization in the Central District</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Design Strategy</h3>\r\nThe design needed to be tailored to a broad range of audience segments. The primary audience was individuals and families living in the Central District who qualify for affordable housing. The secondary audience was community members and small businesses, particularly of pan-African decent, affected by displacement in the Central District. The third audience, was public officials, agencies, and organization who work with affordable housing.\r\n\r\nTo clarify the eligibility requirements for affordable housing and walk applicants through the leasing process, I neatly organized complex leasing information in a format accessible to a broad audience whom are largely unfamiliar with affordable housing regulation in Seattle.\r\n<h3>Design Solution</h3>\r\n[scroller bg-color="LightSlateGrey"]<img class="alignnone wp-image-175 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-cover-refinements_compressed_Page_1.jpg" alt="" width="1224" height="1584" /> <img class="alignnone wp-image-176 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-cover-refinements_compressed_Page_2.jpg" alt="" width="2448" height="1584" /> <img class="alignnone wp-image-177 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-cover-refinements_compressed_Page_3.jpg" alt="" width="2448" height="1584" /> <img class="alignnone wp-image-178 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-cover-refinements_compressed_Page_4.jpg" alt="" width="2448" height="1584" /> <img class="alignnone wp-image-179 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-cover-refinements_compressed_Page_5.jpg" alt="" width="1224" height="1584" />[/scroller]\r\n\r\nThe Capitol Hill Housing Foundation hired me to deliver a single leasing packet of the following items:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>General building information including amenities, photos, and location map</li>\r\n 	<li>Affordable housing process overview</li>\r\n 	<li>Income requirements for applying</li>\r\n 	<li>A timeline of the project development and leasing</li>\r\n 	<li>Frequently Asked Questions</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Design Process</h3>\r\nLeasing affordable housing differs from non-subsidized apartments; and the Liberty Bank Building itself poses a unique application process. While focusing on conceptual development with moodboards, typography and color schemes, I worked with the team to categorize, synthesize and tailor content strategically.\r\n\r\nThe visual design is intuitive and simply explains affordable housing, the application process, and eligibility requirements using accessible language. Visual graphs and tables help applicants interactively determine their eligibility, while a four step visual breakdown walks them through the leasing process. We sourced historic photos from the Liberty Bank partners, and composed them with photos of the new Liberty Bank Building. I coordinated with the client to render a more diverse group of people in the building renderings. I was sure to prioritize contact information; and developed a Frequently Asked Questions spread. I also included a timeline of key dates for the project construction and leasing process.\r\n<h3>Project Impact</h3>\r\nThe layout itself is a huge improvement from the single word document the partners began with. Including photos of the historic Central District and current community events, drastically improved the packets relatability. The use of visual motifs, typographic hierarchy and layout, and brand consistency were driving forces behind achieving project goals.\r\n\r\nThe Capitol Hill Housing Association ensures their approach to each community building is both intentional and affective in targeting individuals in need of affordable housing. Upon beginning this assignment, there were minor tensions rising between community partners as its construction progressed. The success of this collateral project strengthened the Liberty Bank Building partners’ trust in Capitol Hill Housings’ ability to be aware of its context and deliver content that is relevant to this project’s audience.\r\n\r\nThe partners responded very positively to the leasing packet design. The project delivered on schedule and within the project budget. Once the Liberty Bank Building partners begin actively marketing, it is anticipated this leasing packet will allow local community members to become more familiar with the affordable housing application process and give them the confidence to inquire about living at the Liberty Bank Building.\r\n\r\nThe Liberty Bank Building partners utilized the leasing packet to affirmatively market to audiences affected by rapid urbanization. They planned to host local events to build community and pass out these leasing packets to residents in need. The visual design compliments their marketing tactics in a way that communicates the history of the Liberty Bank, expresses the future tone of the Liberty Bank Building, and respects the pan-African community in the Central District.\r\n<h3>Sources</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><a href="http://libertybankbuilding.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Liberty Bank Building</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href="http://www.africatownlandtrust.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Africa Town Land Trust, Central District</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href="https://byrdbarrplace.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Byrd Barr Place</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href="http://david-harris-wkj7.squarespace.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Black Community Impact Alliance</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href="https://www.capitolhillhousing.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Capitol Hill Housing Foundation</a></li>\r\n</ul>', 'The Liberty Bank Building', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '160-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-07-09 18:05:23', '2018-07-09 18:05:23', '', 160, 'http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/160-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(264, 1, '2018-07-09 18:06:28', '2018-07-09 18:06:28', '<span style="font-weight: 400;">I worked as a Digital Designer at the award winning architectural firm SDK Atelier in Irvine, California. I handled a variety of tasks ranging from creating digital color schemes and physical moodboards for client presentations, rendering house plans on a street scene in color with landscaping for city submittal and approval, and plotting basic house floor plans at scale to learn the essentials of AutoCAD. I attained essential knowledge about the process of urban development and architectural design in a fast paced, professional work environment.</span>\r\n\r\n[image_block]\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-200" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/ALIENTO_PRACTICE_PLAN1.jpg" alt="" />\r\n<h4>Aliento CAD Layout</h4>\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">This layout was made using AutoCAD 2016 for mac. Vice President, Dustin Karami, mentored me through the process of measuring an existing plan at scale, then recreating a top view floor plan using the existing plan data.\r\n</span>[/image_block]\r\n\r\n[scroller bg-color="white"]<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-201" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/IMG_3734.jpg" alt="" /><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-202" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/IMG_3736.jpg" alt="" /><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-203" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/IMG_3737.jpg" alt="" /><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-204" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/IMG_3738.jpg" alt="" />[/scroller]\r\n<h3>Sources</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><a href="http://sdkatelier.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">SDK Atelier</a></li>\r\n</ul>', 'SDK Atelier', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '199-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-07-09 18:06:28', '2018-07-09 18:06:28', '', 199, 'http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/199-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(265, 1, '2018-07-09 18:09:38', '2018-07-09 18:09:38', 'I was one of three freelance designers retained by local restaurant owner Kevin Chung to develop brand identity and menu signage for his new restaurant Cheese Meats Bread (CMB) in 2017.\r\n<h3>Background</h3>\r\nA colleague Chris Mercurio leveraged his relationship with Kevin to retain a brand design contract and manage the client relationship. He contracted fellow designer, Kenzie Nicholson, and I to execute the brand design. Kenzie and I collaboratively envisioned a brand identity; developed a handout menu, large format menu and food packaging for CMB’s grand opening.\r\n<h3>Project Challenges &amp; Goals</h3>\r\nCheese Meats Bread is an international take on an american classic—the grilled cheese sandwich. Mr. Chung planned to open in the Uwajimaya Village marketplace in the International District.\r\n<h3>Design Strategy</h3>\r\nDuring the research phase Kenzie and I talked largely about how to add an international flare to an American classic without having the brand be offensive or too intrusive for a largely international audience.\r\n<h3>Design Solution</h3>\r\nKenzie and I worked collaboratively throughout the project brainstorming, concept development, and refinement phases. When executing the final deliverables, kenzie created the typographic pattern and packaging design, while I focused on the large format menu board, small take-out menu, and brand identity style guide.\r\n\r\n[image_block][scroller]<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-185" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CMB_style-guide_8.5x11.jpg" alt="" /><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-188" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CMB-menu_6x11.jpg" alt="" /><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-187" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CMB_menu-board_6x4ft_opt-2.jpg" alt="" />[/scroller]\r\n<h4>Brand style guide</h4>\r\n<h4>6x11 in. takeout menu</h4>\r\n<h4>6x4 ft. menu board</h4>\r\n[/image_block]\r\n<h3>Design Process</h3>\r\nWhile brainstorming and exploring concepts, Kenzie and I provided the client with numerous concepts, each of which approached the CMB brand from a unique lens. Upon listening more closely to general feedback from others and the client’s reaction to our presentation, they liked the variety of font selections we provided, but overall they gravitated towards more simpler fonts and cleaner illustrations. We decided on a typographic solution that used a simple typographic logo mark and a typographic pattern as the primary brand elements with a gooey yellow accent color.\r\n<h3>Project Impact</h3>\r\nWe successfully delivered the brand identity packet to the client on schedule and within our budget. Afterwards, I maintained a positive relationship with the client and both design colleagues. CMB is open today and thriving in Seattle’s International District at the Uwajimaya Village market place.\r\n<h3>Sources</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><a href="https://cheesemeatsbread.life/">Cheese Meats Bread</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/chriselvis/">Client Relations: Chris Mercurio</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/kenzie-nicholson/">Designer: Kenzie Nicholson</a></li>\r\n</ul>', 'Cheese Meats Bread', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '183-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-07-09 18:09:38', '2018-07-09 18:09:38', '', 183, 'http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/183-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(266, 1, '2018-07-09 18:16:30', '2018-07-09 18:16:30', 'Capitol Hill Housing (CHH) is a public corporation organized by the City of Seattle. Their mission is to build vibrant and engaged communities through affordable housing and community development. In total, CHH manages approximately 50 properties, each with eligibility requirements ranging from low-income, elderly, disabled, veteran and other eligibility restricted units.\r\n<h3>Background</h3>\r\nCapitol Hill Housing Resident Service department employs Resident Service Coordinators (RSC) to inform, coordinate and provide resources to its diverse residents. The RSC primarily communicate with residents through information sheets, advertisements on community boards, door-to-door tactics, community, and building events and direct one-on-one contact. They serve as the central resource for all residents living in CHH properties, providing a range of services including general questions, hosting community events and coordinating need-based services such as rental assistance, live-in health care and transportation services to name a few.\r\n<h3>Project Challenges &amp; Goals</h3>\r\nAccording to CHH resident surveys, less than half the residents were aware that CHH provided individualized support through its Resident Services Program. Additionally, the RSC relied heavily on Microsoft word, so it became important to create a template system any RSC could use on any type of computer. As such, the project goals were identified as follows:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Inform residents about RSC and increase awareness of the many services available</li>\r\n 	<li>Simplify the layout and be consistent with the CHH brand</li>\r\n 	<li>Improve the collateral functionality and usability for RSC</li>\r\n 	<li>Improve and increase the visual accessibility for CHH’s diverse residents</li>\r\n 	<li>Improve and increase the trust between resident and RSC in individual communities</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Design Strategy</h3>\r\nTo achieve these goals, I brainstormed the visual design by assessing technical concerns, researching the methods in which RSC communicate with residents and the reviewing the overall brand image and messaging of CHH. To increase overall brand awareness, I set forth to unify the CHH brand image and develop a template system that could be unique for individual properties, yet consistent with the larger CHH brand. Additionally, I created pieces that were simply formatted, easily customizable and implementable by the RSC in each residential community.\r\n<h3>Design Solutions</h3>\r\nThe client hired me to provide graphic design services for five collateral items most utilized by the RSC. The pieces were to be redesigned, while meeting the aforementioned goals in to the five unified, brand consistent templates:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Building Welcome Sheets</li>\r\n 	<li>RSC Persona Sheets</li>\r\n 	<li>Monthly Events Calendar</li>\r\n 	<li>Event Flyers</li>\r\n 	<li>Resource One Sheets</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[image_block]\r\n<img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-49" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE_Resident-Services-poster_11x17-663x1024.jpg" alt="" />\r\n<h4>Resident Services Poster</h4>\r\nIn addition to the five collateral templates, I designed a large format poster to advertise CHH Resident Services. It primarily informs residents of the services available to them. We proposed to mount these posters on community boards in public building spaces, around the building property and within CHH offices. This poster design acts as the outward, public facing representation of the CHH Resident Services available.\r\n[/image_block]\r\n\r\n[image_block][scroller]<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-51" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE_welcome-sheetgeneral_8.5x11.jpg" alt="" /><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-52" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE_welcome-sheetJoeyG_8.5x11.jpg" alt="" /><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-34" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/tmpl_individual-rsc-768x1024.jpg" alt="" /><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-32" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/poster_resident-services-e1530318746544-834x1024.jpg" alt="" />[/scroller]\r\n<h4>Building Welcome and RSC Persona Sheets</h4>\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Upon move in, residents receive a packet which includes the building welcome and RSC persona sheets. The building welcome sheet informs residents about CHH and resources available through the Resident Services program. The RSC persona sheet introduces the specific RS Coordinator supporting the residents’ property. Both these documents are intended to welcome residents and provide them essential resources, contact information, and other important details about CHH and RSC.</span>\r\n[/image_block]\r\n\r\n[image_block][scroller]<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-53" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE-calendar_11x8.5.jpg" alt="" /> <img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-35" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/tmpl_residence-calendar-e1530319018147-1024x803.jpg" alt="" />[/scroller]\r\n<h4>Monthly Events Calendar</h4>\r\nMonthly calendars specific to each property highlight upcoming community events. They are available online, by email and posted in community spaces. After creating a 2018-19 monthly calendar template with updated styles, I added additional content to the footer, specific to each RSC and building property. This allows the RSC to put their contact information and specific building information on the calendars for residents to easily reference.\r\n[/image_block]\r\n\r\n[image_block][scroller]<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-48" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE_event-poster_8.5x11.jpg" alt="" /> <img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-47" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/BLANK_event-flyer_x2_5.5x8.5-1024x791.jpg" alt="" /> <img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-33" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/tmpl_event-flyers-e1530319332673-797x1024.jpg" alt="" />[/scroller]\r\n<h4>Event Flyers</h4>\r\nEvent flyers are posted in community spaces to advertise a variety of events and workshops. For maximum ease of use and flexibility, I designed a variable sidebar layout for things like recurrent event dates and event sign-ups. RSCs can choose between having a single event date or multiple recurring events.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, there is an option for a sign-up content block with a variable height, allowing for maximum customization. I also created a half-sheet event template that reduces event information to its hook, a primary message and call to action, for use by the RSC as handouts for local, building specific events.\r\n[/image_block]\r\n\r\n[image_block][scroller]<img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-50" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE_resource-one-sheet_8.5x11-791x1024.jpg" alt="" /> <img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-36" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/tmpl_resource-one-sheet-e1530319531779-819x1024.jpg" alt="" />[/scroller]\r\n<h4>Resource One Sheets</h4>\r\nThese templates list all relevant contact information for each resource category. I created a typographic system and grid layout that adapts to each collateral template. The system I conceived maintains the appropriate balance between text legibility and readability. This one sheet example is the simplest form of typography and grid layout utilized across every template.\r\n[/image_block]\r\n<h3>Design Process</h3>\r\nIn developing the collateral pieces, the challenges and goals of the client were kept in the forefront. As such, in all steps of the project development the following were considered: awareness and consistency; accessibility; and usability.\r\n<h4>Awareness &amp; Consistency</h4>\r\nConsistency affects people’s awareness and trust of a brand. If residents aren’t clear what the RSC provide and who they are in relation to CHH, then they are likely to have less faith in the services provided. I directly addressed this issue through a systematically implemented visual design. Through use of typography, white space, graphic elements and color, I achieved overall visual consistency between each collateral template.\r\n<h4>Accessibility</h4>\r\nThe visual design compliments the content strategy and does not detract from it. We simplified the text and used language understood by a general audience. I also utilized a relatively large font size to improve legibility for residents with visual impairments. Attention was also paid to color usage, to increase accessibility for color visually impaired people.\r\n<h4>Usability</h4>\r\nTo provide maximum ease of use for the RSC, who may not have a background in design or layout programs, I chose Adobe InDesign to make the templates. The Adobe InDesign has excellent interface with Adobe Acrobat, the program used by the majority of CHH employees. This has resulted in great ease of use for the RSC, allowing for editable content while maintaining overall brand consistency and increased design awareness.\r\n<h3>Project Results</h3>\r\nThe overall response from the Client, CHH employees, Resident Service Coordinators and residents was overwhelmingly positive. The visual design and functionality of my project deliverables exceeded their expectations. In fact, after using the new templates, several RSC requested more variations for the event flyers, resulting in additional project work. In recreating these design pieces for CHH, I created a visual design similar enough to the existing look to maintain the familiarity of the old styles, while drastically improving brand accessibility, functionality, consistency and awareness. Our focus on content strategy, language and visual harmony allowed the simple style to accommodate the diverse audiences with propriety and appeal.\r\n\r\n[scroller]\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-71" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/IMG_3094_small.jpg" alt="Capitol Hill Housing community event" /> <img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-90" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/IMG_2666-768x1024.jpg" alt="" /> <img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-89" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/IMG_2499-1024x768.jpg" alt="" /> <img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-70" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CAPHILLHOUSING-186-1-1024x683.jpg" alt="Ashwin Warrior enters the Capitol Hill Housing offices on 12th Ave." />[/scroller]', 'Capitol Hill Housing Resident Services', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '23-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-07-09 18:16:30', '2018-07-09 18:16:30', '', 23, 'http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/23-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(267, 1, '2018-07-09 18:17:45', '2018-07-09 18:17:45', 'I am a reliable digital designer who learns fast and enjoys organization. I excel at composing and formulating information into clear visuals that demonstrate mature application of design theory and practice. With a diverse background in digital and print design, I work with local businesses to develop impact driven collateral including marketing tools, brand identity, templates, website design, presentations and visual strategies.\r\n\r\nMy experience working with a startup, an architecture studio, designing for Seattle businesses, and serving on a 501(c)(3) board as the Design and Marketing Chair, allowed me the opportunity to gain in depth knowledge about the professional and creative sides of design.\r\n\r\nPeople tell me I am good at\r\n\r\nAsking Questions\r\n\r\nMy process is driven by curiosity. I address challenges creatively by asking questions first. Afterwards, I thoroughly research target markets, audience demographics, typography and design patterns. At the same time, hand sketching and photographic moodboards compliment my research. This part of my process inspires further conceptual development and helps me understand the variables involved — to properly execute a visual strategy that achieves the project goals.\r\n\r\nIteration &amp; Variation\r\n\r\nI use an iterative design process to explore many design concepts. Team critiques are an important component to iteration. It opens up dialogue between the design concept and its stakeholders. Brainstorming is another tactic I utilize in my workflow to help teams visualize and orient towards a design concept. These conversations inform my process and serve further conceptual development.\r\nOrganization\r\nWhether it’s my desk space, a quarterly marketing plan, or comprehensive designs, I maintain an organized workspace and accessible workflow. My design process adapts to new project variables easily. This enables me to simplify the process for clients and provide them with resources that support team goals.\r\n\r\n[column_wrap count="2"] [column class="full"]\r\n<h2>I am confident working in</h2>\r\n[/column] [column]\r\n<h3>Industry Knowledge</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Branding design and positioning</li>\r\n 	<li>Visual design for print and digital media</li>\r\n 	<li>Marketing advertisements and campaign design</li>\r\n 	<li>Social media marketing</li>\r\n 	<li>Typography and calligraphy</li>\r\n 	<li>Photography and video editing</li>\r\n 	<li>Project Management</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/column] [column]\r\n<h3>Tools &amp; Languages</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Microsoft Office (Word and Excel)</li>\r\n 	<li>Adobe Creative Suite (InDesign, Photoshop, Illustrator)</li>\r\n 	<li>HTML5 and CSS3</li>\r\n 	<li>Javascript and jQuery</li>\r\n 	<li>PHP Wordpress Development</li>\r\n 	<li>Google Analytics</li>\r\n 	<li>Search Engine Optimization</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/column] [/column_wrap]\r\n<h3>In my free time</h3>\r\nFind me outside rock climbing and camping with my friends—somewhere beautiful, surrounded by nature. When i’m not outdoors, I’m exploring my community—probably trying one of the hundred coffee shops in Seattle. Elliott Bay Bookstore is my go to place to read, research, sketch, and code. In my cozy home studio, I like to improve on my design abilities, bind books, practice calligraphy, and spend time with the lovely <a href="http://samschnabel.com/">Sam </a><a href="http://samschnabel.com/">Schnabel</a>. Whether work or play, staying active and keeping close to family and friends, fuels my creativity.\r\n\r\n[scroller] personal pickers of: rock climbing, hiking, Italy book binding, calligraphy [/scroller]', 'About Me', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '9-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-07-09 18:17:45', '2018-07-09 18:17:45', '', 9, 'http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/9-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
