(286, 1, '2018-07-09 21:10:27', '2018-07-09 21:10:27', '<h3>Background</h3>\r\nFor a service learning assignment, I formed a design team with colleagues, Alicia Smith and Ivy Ye. We partnered with the Capitol Hill Arts District (CH Arts District) to design an awareness campaign that coincided with their new website.\r\n<h3>Project Challenges &amp; Goals</h3>\r\nAccording to a recent neighborhood survey, the majority of residents were unaware that Capitol Hill Arts District exists. It was the first neighborhood to be named as part of the Arts &amp; Cultural Districts program by the Seattle City Government (2014). CH Arts District launched their new website in 2017 to elevate its presence. My team’s primary goal was to build off the visual tone established on their website and to increase local community’s awareness of the CH Arts District.\r\n\r\nAnother key challenge for this design assignment was to manage, plan, and coordinate a collaborative design with a team. As the Design Team Lead, I worked closely with Alicia and Ivy to delegate and deliver to our client a comprehensive collateral design and marketing plan.\r\n<h3>Design Strategy</h3>\r\nOur team collaboratively wrote and developed an original marketing campaign. We focused on the environmental and neighborhood aspect of the CH Arts District by designing the marketing collateral as elements of a wayfinding system—to compliment pre-existing brand elements.\r\n\r\nFor example, CH Arts District recently installed new road signs that include their logo on the District perimeter. This improved drivers’ awareness of the Arts District brand and geographic location. We capitalize on their approach buy advertising the large format posters along the perimeter. This expanded the wayfinding signage for pedestrians and increase people’s perception of the CH Arts District physical boundary.\r\n\r\nInside of the CH Arts District, we empowered community partners to facilitate the neighborhood brand. We distributed small format postcards and stickers to community partners and asked them to display and sell them within their business.\r\n\r\nDigital assets, like neighborhood photographs and Facebook cover photos, expanded the CH Arts District presence online. Additionally, the hashtags #NowEntering and #CapitolHillArtsDistrict were applied to the collateral to track the conversation online.\r\n<h3>Design Solution</h3>\r\nThe Capitol Hill Arts District requested that we deliver to them each the following:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>11x17 in. poster design</li>\r\n 	<li>6x4 in. postcard design</li>\r\n 	<li>4x4 in. round sticker</li>\r\n 	<li>Facebook cover photo</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[scroller bg-color="white"]<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-224" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_poster-mockup-side-by-side.jpg" alt="" /><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-225" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_poster-telephone-pole-01.jpg" alt="" /><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-226" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_poster-telephone-pole-02.jpg" alt="" />[/scroller]\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-220" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/Capitol-Hill-Arts-District-social-media-mockup.jpg" alt="" />\r\n<h3>Design Process</h3>\r\nAs the Design Team Lead, it was my responsibility to understand the scope of work to be done, coordinate a schedule between the designers and our client, delegate tasks to each team member, and maintain a positive focus on the project goals and deliverables.\r\n\r\nThe design process included reviewing existing collateral and advertisements, and brainstorming ways to expand up the existing wayfinding signage. Utilizing over 50 photos of public artworks and murals within the Arts district, our team developed initial sketches and defined our concept. Next, we developed the postcard and poster content and produced a series of layouts and sticker designs. The photographs were also used to create social media cover photos. We presented refined concepts to the client for final design edits and then approval.\r\n\r\nThe project scope also included researching of local printers and advertisement companies, coordinating and securing price estimates for printing the collateral and posting flyers around Capitol Hill. Lastly, we presented our marketing campaign design to the Arts District Steering Committee.\r\n<h3>Project Impact</h3>\r\nOur team presented the campaign to the Arts District Steering Committee and recommended a course of action for marketing the CH Arts District. The committee response was overwhelmingly positive.\r\n\r\nThey appreciate the versatility of the design system we made. The text content was minimal and remained consistent across the collateral. The CH Arts District logo was prominently featured, as they requested; while the interchangeable background photos of CH Arts District murals highlighted the local community. The interchangeable backgrounds empowered the committee to swap out photographs with other options we provided. We even proposed to source background photos from district partners and community members to delivered more community value. This was a unique approach to the and CH Arts District committee appreciated the variety and adaptability we provided them.\r\n\r\nThe marketing collateral served as advertisements and aided wayfinding. The large format posters were put along the perimeter of the district to identify its boundary, while personal collateral items were used inside partner locations. The collateral did a solid job notifying people they were entering a new city neighborhood and complemented existing CH Arts District brand signage.\r\n\r\nPostcards and stickers provided and interact marketing tactic that improved peoples perception and engagement with the CH Arts District. In addition, the content was focused and clearly promoted shared art and cultural values. By diversifying the type of collateral and the locations they were marketed, it allowed more audience touch points to increase the campaigns impact.\r\n\r\nTo our excitement, many businesses endorsed our efforts to market the CH Arts District. They liked having the responsibility as a community partner to facilitate the neighborhood’s brand. Some community partners even opted to put the poster advertisement in their window.\r\n\r\nThe committee accepted our proposed marketing plan and the posters, stickers, and postcards were successfully promoted in the Capitol Hill Arts District throughout the summer of 2017.\r\n<h3>Sources</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><a href="http://capitolhillarts.org/now-entering/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Capitol Hill Arts, Now Entering campaign page</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href="https://segd.org/what-wayfinding/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">What is Wayfinding? — Seattle Environmental Graphic Design</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[column_wrap count="2"]\r\n\r\n[column]\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-223" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_postcards-front-01.jpg" alt="" />\r\n[/column]\r\n\r\n[column]\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-222 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_postcards-back.jpg" alt="" width="2812" height="2824" />\r\n\r\n[/column]\r\n\r\n[/column_wrap]\r\n\r\n[column_wrap count="9"]\r\n[column]\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-234 size-thumbnail" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-dark-150x150.jpg" alt="" width="150" height="150" />\r\n[/column][column]\r\n<img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-227 alignnone" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-1-red-150x150.jpg" alt="" />\r\n[/column][column]\r\n<img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-228 alignnone" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-2-orange-150x150.jpg" alt="" />\r\n[/column][column]\r\n<img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-229 alignnone" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-3-yellow-150x150.jpg" alt="" />\r\n[/column][column]\r\n<img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-230 alignnone" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-4-green-150x150.jpg" alt="" />\r\n[/column][column]\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-231 size-thumbnail" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-5-teal-150x150.jpg" alt="" width="150" height="150" />\r\n[/column][column]\r\n<img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-232 alignnone" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-6-blue-150x150.jpg" alt="" />\r\n[/column][column]\r\n<img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-233 alignnone" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-7-purple-150x150.jpg" alt="" />\r\n[/column][column]\r\n<img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-235 alignnone" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CHAD_stickers_4in-light-150x150.jpg" alt="" />\r\n[/column]\r\n[/column_wrap]', 'Capitol Hill Arts District', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '217-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-07-09 21:10:27', '2018-07-09 21:10:27', '', 217, 'http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/217-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(287, 1, '2018-07-09 23:51:05', '2018-07-09 23:51:05', 'For the Capitol Hill Housing leasing department, I conceptualized, designed and developed a leasing packet for an affordable housing development in the Central District called the Liberty Bank Building. The building is a multi-use apartment complex with entirely low-income eligible units and over 2,500 square feet of commercial space for local businesses. It is currently under construction and scheduled to open February 2019.\n<h3>Background</h3>The Liberty Bank Building is the result of a collective partnership between Africa Town Central District, Byrd Barr Place, Black Community Impact Alliance, the Capitol Hill Housing Foundation, local community leaders and founders of the Liberty Bank. This historic project aspires to preserve the legacy of <em>the Liberty Bank</em>, "the first Black-owned bank west of the Mississippi, founded as a community response to redlining and disinvestment in Central Seattle" (libertybankbuilding.org).\n\nHistorically, the City government divested from the Central District. This segregated community became a hub for pan-African and migrant community culture. Today it is experiencing rapid urban development, and as rent increases faster than the existing community members are able to afford, they become displaced from their homes.\n\nThe Liberty Bank Building is designed to be affordable to everyday people, and aspires to continue to support the community for years to come. We wanted to highlight this legacy, preserve the existing identity of the Central District, and steward in a new generation of community engagement.\n<h3>Project Challenges &amp; Goals</h3>Existing Liberty Bank material, while resourceful, was lengthy and complex, making it impractical for the target audience. A key assignment for this project was to create leasing content that would be understandable and usable for <em>all members</em> of the community—<em>it needed to be accessible</em>.\n\nThe leasing packet design was heavily influenced by all these factors. The project goals were:\n<ul>\n 	<li>to clarify the eligibility requirements for affordable housing</li>\n 	<li>walk applicants through the leasing process and timeline for the Liberty Bank Building</li>\n 	<li>affirmatively market to audiences affected by rapid urbanization in the Central District</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Design Strategy</h3>The design needed to be tailored to a broad range of audience segments. The primary audience was individuals and families living in the Central District who qualify for affordable housing. The secondary audience was community members and small businesses, particularly of pan-African decent, affected by rapidly rising rent. The third audience, was public officials, agencies, and organization who work in the housing marketplace.\n\nTo clarify the eligibility requirements for affordable housing and walk applicants through the leasing process, I neatly organized complex leasing information in a format accessible to a broad audience whom are largely unfamiliar with affordable housing regulation in Seattle, but have a deeply rooted history in the Central District.\n<h3>Design Solution</h3>[scroller bg-color="LightSlateGrey"]<img src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-cover-refinements_compressed_Page_1.jpg" class="alignnone wp-image-175 size-full" height="1584" alt="" width="1224"><img src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-cover-refinements_compressed_Page_2.jpg" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-176" height="1584" alt="" width="2448"><img src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-cover-refinements_compressed_Page_3.jpg" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-177" height="1584" alt="" width="2448"><img src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-cover-refinements_compressed_Page_4.jpg" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-178" height="1584" alt="" width="2448"><img src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-cover-refinements_compressed_Page_5.jpg" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-179" height="1584" alt="" width="1224">[/scroller]\n\nThe Capitol Hill Housing Foundation hired me to deliver a single leasing packet of the following items:\n<ul>\n 	<li>General building information including amenities, photos, and location map</li>\n 	<li>Affordable housing process overview</li>\n 	<li>Income requirements for applying</li>\n 	<li>A timeline of the project development and leasing process</li>\n 	<li>Frequently Asked Questions sheet</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Design Process</h3>Leasing affordable housing differs from non-subsidized apartments; and the Liberty Bank Building itself poses a unique application process. While focusing on conceptual development with moodboards, typography and color schemes, I worked with the team to categorize, synthesize and tailor content strategically.\n\nThe visual design is intuitive and simply explains affordable housing, the application process, and eligibility requirements use accessible language. Visual graphs and tables help applicants interactively determine their eligibility, while a four step visual breakdown walks them through the leasing process.\n\nWe sourced historic photos from the Liberty Bank partners, and composed them with photos of the new Liberty Bank Building. I coordinated with the client to render a more diverse group of people in the building renderings. I was sure to prioritize contact information; and developed a Frequently Asked Questions spread. I also included a timeline of key dates for the project construction and leasing process.\n<h3>Project Impact</h3>The layout itself is a huge improvement from the single word document the partners began with. Including photos of the historic Central District and current community events, drastically improved the packets relatability. The use of visual motifs, typographic hierarchy and layout, and brand consistency were driving forces behind achieving project goals.\n\nThe partners responded very positively to the leasing packet design. The project delivered on schedule and within the project budget. Once the Liberty Bank Building partners begin actively marketing, it is anticipated this leasing packet will allow local community members to become more familiar with the affordable housing application process and give them the confidence to inquire about living at the Liberty Bank Building.\n\nThe Liberty Bank Building partners utilized the leasing packet to affirmatively market to audiences affected by rapid urbanization. They plan to host local events to build community and pass out these leasing packets to residents in need. The visual design compliments their marketing tactics in a way that communicates the history of the Liberty Bank, expresses the future tone of the Liberty Bank Building, and respects the pan-African community in the Central District.\n<h3>Sources</h3>\n<ul>\n 	<li><a href="http://libertybankbuilding.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Liberty Bank Building</a></li>\n 	<li><a href="http://www.africatownlandtrust.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Africa Town Land Trust, Central District</a></li>\n 	<li><a href="https://byrdbarrplace.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Byrd Barr Place</a></li>\n 	<li><a href="http://david-harris-wkj7.squarespace.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Black Community Impact Alliance</a></li>\n 	<li><a href="https://www.capitolhillhousing.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Capitol Hill Housing Foundation</a></li>\n</ul>', 'The Liberty Bank Building', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '160-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-07-09 23:51:05', '2018-07-09 23:51:05', '', 160, 'http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/160-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 