(329, 1, '2018-07-12 18:03:26', '2018-07-12 18:03:26', 'For the Capitol Hill Housing leasing department, I conceptualized, designed and developed a leasing packet for an affordable housing development in the Central District called the Liberty Bank Building. The building is a multi-use apartment complex with entirely low-income eligible units and over 2,500 square feet of commercial space for local businesses. It is currently under construction and scheduled to open February 2019.\r\n<h3>Background</h3>\r\nThe Liberty Bank Building is the result of a collective partnership between Africa Town Central District, Byrd Barr Place, Black Community Impact Alliance, the Capitol Hill Housing Foundation, local community leaders and founders of the Liberty Bank. This historic project aspires to preserve the legacy of <em>the Liberty Bank</em>, "the first Black-owned bank west of the Mississippi, founded as a community response to redlining and disinvestment in Central Seattle" (libertybankbuilding.org).\r\n\r\nHistorically, the City government divested from the Central District. This segregated community became a hub for pan-African and migrant community culture. Today it is experiencing rapid urban development, and as rent increases faster than the existing community members are able to afford, they become displaced from their homes.\r\n\r\nThe Liberty Bank Building is designed to be affordable for everyday people, and continues to support the community for years to come. We wanted to highlight this legacy, preserve the existing identity of the Central District, and steward in a new generation of community engagement.\r\n<h3>Project Challenges &amp; Goals</h3>\r\nExisting Liberty Bank material, while resourceful, was lengthy and complex, making it impractical for the target audience. A key assignment for this project was to create leasing content that would be understandable and usable for <em>all members</em> of the community—<em>it needed to be accessible</em>.\r\n\r\nThe leasing packet design was heavily influenced by all these factors. The project goals were:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>to clarify the eligibility requirements for affordable housing</li>\r\n 	<li>walk applicants through the leasing process and timeline for the Liberty Bank Building</li>\r\n 	<li>affirmatively market to audiences affected by rapid urbanization in the Central District</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Design Strategy</h3>\r\nThe design needed to be tailored to a broad range of audience segments. The primary audience was individuals and families living in the Central District who qualify for affordable housing. The secondary audience was community members and small businesses, particularly of pan-African decent, affected by rapidly rising rent. The third audience, was public officials, agencies, and organization who work in the housing marketplace.\r\n\r\nTo clarify the eligibility requirements for affordable housing and walk applicants through the leasing process, I neatly organized complex leasing information in a format accessible to a broad audience whom are largely unfamiliar with affordable housing regulation in Seattle, but have a deeply rooted history in the Central District.\r\n<h3>Design Solution</h3>\r\n[scroller bg-color="LightSlateGrey"]\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-307 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-refinements_spread_1.jpg" alt="" width="1275" height="1650" /> <img class="alignnone wp-image-308 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-refinements_spread_2.jpg" alt="" width="2550" height="1650" /> <img class="alignnone wp-image-309 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-refinements_spread_3.jpg" alt="" width="2550" height="1650" /> <img class="alignnone wp-image-310 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-refinements_spread_4.jpg" alt="" width="2550" height="1650" /> <img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-311" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018-05-04_LBB-leasing-packet-refinements_spread_5.jpg" alt="" />\r\n[/scroller]\r\n\r\nThe Capitol Hill Housing Foundation hired me to deliver a single leasing packet of the following items:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>General building information including amenities, photos, and location map</li>\r\n 	<li>Affordable housing process overview</li>\r\n 	<li>Income requirements for applying</li>\r\n 	<li>A timeline of the project development and leasing process</li>\r\n 	<li>Frequently Asked Questions sheet</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Design Process</h3>\r\nLeasing affordable housing differs from non-subsidized apartments; and the Liberty Bank Building itself poses a unique application process. While focusing on conceptual development with moodboards, typography and color schemes, I worked with the team to categorize, synthesize and tailor content strategically.\r\n\r\nThe visual design is intuitive and simply explains affordable housing, the application process, and eligibility requirements use accessible language. Visual graphs and tables help applicants interactively determine their eligibility, while a four step visual breakdown walks them through the leasing process.\r\n\r\nWe sourced historic photos from the Liberty Bank partners, and composed them with photos of the new Liberty Bank Building. I coordinated with the client to render a more diverse group of people in the building renderings. I was sure to prioritize contact information; and developed a Frequently Asked Questions spread. I also included a timeline of key dates for the project construction and leasing process.\r\n<h3>Project Impact</h3>\r\nThe layout itself is a huge improvement from the single word document the partners began with. Including photos of the historic Central District and current community events, drastically improved the packet\'s relatability. The use of visual motifs, typographic hierarchy and layout, and brand consistency were driving forces behind achieving project goals.\r\n\r\nThe partners responded very positively to the leasing packet design. The project delivered on schedule and within budget. Once the Liberty Bank Building partners begin actively marketing, it is anticipated this leasing packet will allow local community members to become more familiar with the affordable housing application process and give them the confidence to inquire about living at the Liberty Bank Building.\r\n\r\nThe Liberty Bank Building partners utilized the leasing packet to affirmatively market to audiences affected by rapid urbanization. They plan to host local events to build community and pass out these leasing packets to residents in need. The visual design compliments their marketing tactics in a way that communicates the history of the Liberty Bank, expresses the future tone of the Liberty Bank Building, and respects the pan-African community in the Central District.\r\n<h3>Sources</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><a href="http://libertybankbuilding.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Liberty Bank Building</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href="http://www.africatownlandtrust.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Africa Town Land Trust, Central District</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href="https://byrdbarrplace.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Byrd Barr Place</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href="http://david-harris-wkj7.squarespace.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Black Community Impact Alliance</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href="https://www.capitolhillhousing.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Capitol Hill Housing Foundation</a></li>\r\n</ul>', 'The Liberty Bank Building', 'For the Capitol Hill Housing leasing department, I conceptualized, designed and developed a leasing packet for an affordable housing development in the Central District called the Liberty Bank Building.', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '160-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-07-12 18:03:26', '2018-07-12 18:03:26', '', 160, 'http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/160-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(330, 1, '2018-07-12 18:04:13', '2018-07-12 18:04:13', 'Capitol Hill Housing (CHH) is a public corporation organized by the City of Seattle. Their mission is to build vibrant and engaged communities through affordable housing and community development. In total, CHH manages approximately 50 properties, each with eligibility requirements ranging from low-income, elderly, disabled, veteran and other eligibility restricted units.\r\n\r\n[image_block]\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-49 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE_Resident-Services-poster_11x17.jpg" alt="" width="792" height="1224" />\r\n<h4>Resident Services Poster</h4>\r\nI designed a large format poster to advertise CHH Resident Services. It primarily informs residents of the services available to them. We proposed to mount these posters on community boards in public building spaces, around the building property and within CHH offices. This poster design acts as the outward, public facing representation of the CHH Resident Services.\r\n[/image_block]\r\n<h3>Background</h3>\r\nCapitol Hill Housing Resident Service department employs Resident Service Coordinators (RSC) to inform, coordinate and provide resources to its diverse residents. The RSC primarily communicate with residents through information sheets, advertisements on community boards, door-to-door tactics, community, and building events and direct one-on-one contact. They serve as the central resource for all residents living in CHH properties, providing a range of services including general questions, hosting community events and coordinating need-based services such as rental assistance, live-in health care and transportation services to name a few.\r\n<h3>Project Challenges &amp; Goals</h3>\r\nAccording to CHH resident surveys, less than half the residents were aware that CHH provided individualized support through its Resident Services Program. Additionally, the RSC relied heavily on Microsoft word, so it became important to create a template system any RSC could use on any type of computer. As such, the project goals were identified as follows:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Inform residents about RSC and increase awareness of the many services available</li>\r\n 	<li>Simplify the layout and be consistent with the CHH brand</li>\r\n 	<li>Improve the collateral functionality and usability for RSC</li>\r\n 	<li>Improve and increase the visual accessibility for CHH’s diverse residents</li>\r\n 	<li>Improve and increase the trust between resident and RSC in individual communities</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Design Strategy</h3>\r\nTo achieve these goals, I brainstormed the visual design by assessing technical concerns, researching the methods in which RSC communicate with residents, and reviewed the overall brand image and messaging of CHH. To increase overall brand awareness, I set forth to develop a template system that is unique for individual properties, yet consistent with the larger CHH brand. Additionally, my deliverables were simply formatted and easily customizable for the RSC.\r\n<h3>Design Solutions</h3>\r\nThe client hired me to provide graphic design services for five collateral items most utilized by the RSC. The existing collateral was redesigned to met the aforementioned goals into five unified, brand consistent templates:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Building Welcome Sheets</li>\r\n 	<li>RSC Persona Sheets</li>\r\n 	<li>Monthly Events Calendar</li>\r\n 	<li>Event Flyers</li>\r\n 	<li>Resource One Sheets</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[image_block][scroller]<img class="alignnone wp-image-51 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE_welcome-sheetgeneral_8.5x11.jpg" alt="" /><img class="alignnone wp-image-52 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE_welcome-sheetJoeyG_8.5x11.jpg" alt="" width="612" height="792" /><img class="alignnone wp-image-34 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/tmpl_individual-rsc.jpg" alt="" width="2448" height="3264" /><img class="alignnone wp-image-32 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/poster_resident-services-e1530318746544.jpg" alt="" width="2366" height="2904" />[/scroller]\r\n<h4>Building Welcome and RSC Persona Sheets</h4>\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Upon move in, residents receive a packet which includes the building welcome and RSC persona sheets. The building welcome sheet informs residents about CHH and resources available through the Resident Services program. The RSC persona sheet introduces the specific RS Coordinator supporting the residents’ property. Both these documents are intended to welcome residents and provide them essential resources, contact information, and other important details about CHH and RSC.</span>\r\n[/image_block]\r\n\r\n[image_block][scroller]<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-53" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE-calendar_11x8.5.jpg" alt="" /><img class="alignnone wp-image-35 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/tmpl_residence-calendar-e1530319018147.jpg" alt="" width="2986" height="2341" />[/scroller]\r\n<h4>Monthly Events Calendar</h4>\r\nMonthly calendars specific to each property highlight upcoming community events. They are available online, by email and posted in community spaces. After creating a 2018-19 monthly calendar template with updated styles, I added additional content to the footer, for each RSC and building property. This allows the RSC to put their contact information and specific building information on the calendars for residents to easily reference.\r\n[/image_block]\r\n\r\n[image_block][scroller]<img class="alignnone wp-image-48 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE_event-poster_8.5x11.jpg" alt="" width="612" height="792" /><img class="alignnone wp-image-47 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/BLANK_event-flyer_x2_5.5x8.5.jpg" alt="" width="2200" height="1700" /><img class="alignnone wp-image-33 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/tmpl_event-flyers-e1530319332673.jpg" alt="" width="2325" height="2986" />[/scroller]\r\n<h4>Event Flyers</h4>\r\nEvent flyers posted in community spaces advertise a variety of events and workshops. For maximum ease of use and flexibility, I designed a variable sidebar layout for things like recurrent dates and event sign-ups. RSCs can choose between having a single event date or multiple recurring events, both, or neither.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, there is an option for a sign-up content block with a variable height, allowing for maximum customization. I also created a half-sheet event template that reduces event information to its hook, a primary message and call to action, for use by the RSC as handouts for local, building specific events.\r\n[/image_block]\r\n\r\n[image_block][scroller]<img class="alignnone wp-image-50 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/SAMPLE_resource-one-sheet_8.5x11.jpg" alt="" width="1700" height="2200" /><img class="alignnone wp-image-36 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/tmpl_resource-one-sheet-e1530319531779.jpg" alt="" width="2309" height="2888" />[/scroller]\r\n<h4>Resource One Sheets</h4>\r\nThese templates list all relevant contact information for each resource category. I created a typographic system and grid layout that adapts to each collateral template. The system I conceived maintains the appropriate balance between text legibility and readability. This one sheet example is the simplest form of typography and grid layout utilized across every template.\r\n[/image_block]\r\n<h3>Design Process</h3>\r\nThe challenges and client\'s goals were kept at the forefront of my process while designing the collateral. During each step of the project, the following were considered: consistency; accessibility; and usability.\r\n<h4>Consistency</h4>\r\nConsistency affects people’s awareness and trust of a brand. If residents aren’t clear what the RSC provide and who they are in relation to CHH, then they are likely to have less faith in the services provided. I directly addressed this issue through a systematically implemented visual design. Through use of typography, white space, graphic elements and color, I achieved overall visual consistency between all collateral templates.\r\n<h4>Accessibility</h4>\r\nThe visual design compliments the content strategy and does not detract from it. We simplified the text and used language understood by a general audience. I also utilized a relatively large font size to improve legibility and tested the color contrast, to ensure residents with visual impairments could view the content.\r\n<h4>Usability</h4>\r\nTo provide maximum ease of use for the RSC, who may not have a background in design or layout programs, I chose Adobe InDesign to make the templates. The Adobe InDesign has excellent interface with Adobe Acrobat, a program used by the majority of CHH employees. This resulted in great ease of use for the RSC, allowing for editable content while maintaining overall brand consistency.\r\n<h3>Project Results</h3>\r\nThe overall response from the Client, CHH employees, Resident Service Coordinators and residents was overwhelmingly positive. The visual design and functionality of my project deliverables exceeded their expectations. In fact, after using the new templates, several RSC requested more variations for the event flyers, resulting in additional project work.\r\n\r\nWhile redesigning the RSC collateral, I created a visual design inspired by the existing CHH brand. It maintained the familiarity of the old styles, while drastically improving RSC brand accessibility, usability, and consistency. Our focus on content strategy, language and visual harmony allowed the collateral to accommodate the diverse audiences with propriety and appeal.\r\n\r\n[scroller]\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-71 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/IMG_3094_small.jpg" alt="Capitol Hill Housing community event" width="500" height="333" /><img class="alignnone wp-image-90 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/IMG_2666.jpg" alt="" width="1200" height="1600" /><img class="alignnone wp-image-89 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/IMG_2499.jpg" alt="" width="1600" height="1200" /><img class="alignnone wp-image-70 size-full" src="http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/wp-content/uploads/CAPHILLHOUSING-186-1.jpg" alt="Ashwin Warrior enters the Capitol Hill Housing offices on 12th Ave." width="3000" height="2000" />[/scroller]', 'Capitol Hill Housing Resident Services', 'The Capitol Hill Housing Resident Services department needed brand collateral redesign, in response to many residents indicating they are unaware of Resident Services Coordinators and the resources they provide.', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '23-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-07-12 18:04:13', '2018-07-12 18:04:13', '', 23, 'http://localhost:8888/JoeyGrable.com/2018_wp-grunt/23-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
